<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     11-25 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice goofed, but a near-frantic woman found
a judge who was sensitive to her holiday plight, despite his tough
reputation.
   State Judge J. Taylor Phillips said he found the woman in tears
as she was going from courthouse door to courthouse door trying to
find one open.
   The Florida woman, who had driven from Jacksonville, Fla., had
been ordered to be in Phillips' court ``without fail'' Friday
morning or risk being held in contempt, he said.
   But the person who wrote the summons was in error. The
courthouse was closed Friday for the Thanksgiving holiday.
   By chance, Phillips had come in to his office to catch up on
some work.
   The judge said the woman, whom he did not identify, told him she
was arrested in Macon a few weeks earlier on a minor marijuana
possession charge. Phillips, who has a reputation as being a tough
judge in drug cases, said he would fine her the usual $250.
   ``Well, you've got to accommodate folks,'' the judge said.
``Life's not meant to just stomp folks down. The longer I live, the
more convinced I am of that.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Gov. Rose Mofford isn't concerned that
Soviet President Mikahail Gorbachev outranks her in a new poll of
Phoenix-area residents _ as long as he doesn't run next year.
   ``The Governor said it doesn't make any difference as long as
he's not in the primary or the general election in 1990,'' press
secretary Vada Manager said Friday after a poll showed Gorbachev
and U.S. President George Bush ahead of Mrs. Mofford and every
other state official in the survey.
   Bush got approval ratings from 62 percent of survey respondents,
while Gorbachev got a favorable appraisal from 56 percent.
   The telephone survey of Maricopa County residents conducted this
month by the Behavior Research Center showed 44 percent of the
respondents believed Mrs. Mofford was doing a good or excellent job.
   The survey was based on 609 interviews with adult heads of
household. Pollsters said it had a margin of error of plus or minus
4 percent.
</TEXT>
