<DOCNO> AP891125-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0045EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-Shacks     11-25 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Shacks,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake of '89 Shakes Preservationist of '06 `Big One'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The quake of '89 rattled the director of an
organization dedicated to preserving the little shacks that housed
refugees from the earthquake and fire of '06.
   Jane Cryan, who founded the Society for the Preservation and
Appreciation of San Francisco Refugee Shacks, has decided to pull
up stakes and leave quake-prone California.
   ``This little society, born of the quake, has died of another,''
said Cryan, who founded the organization after she unknowingly
bought a refugee shack in the early 1980s.
   Cryan, 47, said the Oct. 17 earthquake that hit Northern
California ``threw me for a loop.''
   ``I have decided to begin life anew in my home state of
Wisconsin and am returning to my ancestral town of Oshkosh,'' said
Cryan, who also lost her job as an administrative assistant shortly
after the quake.
   ``San Francisco will undoubtedly undergo seismic upgrades that
will obliterate the shacks,'' she said. ``I couldn't bear to be
around to see it.''
   More than 60 of the 5,610 redwood cottages known to exist are
still standing, said Cryan. The cottages, some as small as 10 by 14
feet, were designed by Army engineers and built with federal funds
and donations in public parks and squares. There were 11 shack
camps around the city.
   The families were given the cottages when they moved the
structures to private land.
   There was no Richter scale when the quake hit on April 18, 1906,
but the magnitude was later figured to be 8.3. The quake and the
fire that followed killed somewhere from 700 to 2,000 people.
   Last month's temblor measured 7.1 and killed 67 people, more
than half of them on a freeway that collapsed in Oakland.
   The shacks were put into service after the 1906 quake and fire
while 25,000 people were still living in canvas Army tents in parks
around San Francisco.
   After living in the shack cities, more than 5,000 families
resettled and took their shacks with them, dragging them away with
horses. The structures ended up scattered all over the city.
   Cryan was living in one of the old cottages and didn't even know
it.
   ``Someone told me the house was a refugee cottage and I checked
it out,'' she said. ``That was about three months after I moved in.
It was three of them joined together. I got it recognized as a
landmark.''
   Cryan has accumulated shack doors, windows and other memorabilia
through the years.
   She's ``passing the society's torch'' to her friend Jo Falcon,
who is storing the items that include an architectural model of a
shack town of 22 cottages.
   Cryan says the shacks were ``the original modular housing.''
   ``They feel like homes, they make you feel safe and cozy, even
though they're small.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
