<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra Bjt   11-25 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, Bjt,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Appeal Dismissal of Iran-Contra Case Against CIA Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors are asking a federal appeals court
to revive the criminal case against a former CIA station chief in
Central America who was caught up in the Iran-Contra affair.
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va.,
dismissed criminal charges against Joseph Fernandez on Friday,
ruling Fernandez could not get a fair trial because the Justice
Department barred use of classified materials considered important
to the defense.
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh's office quickly filed a
notice of appeal with the U.S. Court of Appeals in Richmond, Va.
Prosecutors said the ruling places Fernandez outside the law.
   ``We believe that all citizens _ including high-ranking
government officials involved in covert operations _ should be
accountable to the law,'' said associate independent counsel
Laurence Shtasel, who is prosecuting the Fernandez case.
   Prosecutors are appealing both the judge's ruling Friday and his
July decision to reject proposed substitutions for the secrets.
   Fernandez assisted former White House aide Oliver North's secret
Contra resupply effort during a congressional ban on U.S. military
aid to the Contras. The effort in Central America was financed
partly by diverted profits from secret arms sales to Iran.
   Fernandez was charged with two counts of obstruction of justice
and two counts of making false statements.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Wednesday barred courtroom
use of classified materials Fernandez said would prove his case.
The secrets _ said by the judge to be ``essential to this
defendant'' _ concern CIA stations and programs in Central America.
   Fernandez has claimed some activities to help North were
intertwined with U.S.-assisted plans by Costa Rica against possible
invasion by Nicaragua. Fernandez says, for example, that he did not
lie when he told the CIA inspector general an airstrip built by the
North network was initiated by the Costa Rican government.
   Fernandez said after Hilton's ruling Friday that he feared CIA
operatives performing ``legitimate duties'' could be subjected to a
``politically motivated prosecution.''
   ``That is a chilling message to people who put their lives on
the line every day,'' he said.
   Iran-Contra prosecutors have said much of the classified
information the government is protecting constitutes ``fictional
secrets'' which have been revealed publicly before.
   But Fernandez said the secrets would compromise national
security and added that its disclosure would have compromised
intelligence sources.
   Thornburgh suggested an agreement could be reached with Walsh to
allow a trial for Fernandez.
   ``I continue to believe that this case can be tried without
compromising the defendant's right to a fair trial or the national
security of this country,'' he said in a statement Friday. ``The
independent counsel and I agree that the district court's earlier
rejection of substitutions and alternatives to the release of
classified material constituted reversible error.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
