<FIRST>r w PM-Cheney-NATO     11-25 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheney-NATO,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney to Attend NATO Defense Meeting in Brussels Nov. 28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney is beginning a
trip to Europe today that will include discussions of fast-moving
events in Eastern Europe with NATO defense ministers at a meeting
in Brussels.
   Cheney is traveling first to the Netherlands, where he will meet
with the Dutch prime minister and visit an American military unit
before proceeding to Belgium for the annual NATO Defense Planning
Committee meeting Nov. 28-29.
   A senior administration official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the NATO agenda includes discussion of issues such
as cost-sharing, arms control and defense planning and the ongoing
negotiations to reduce conventional forces in Europe.
   But, the official added, ``Overwhelming the agenda is what's
going on in Eastern Europe. ... Our European friends feel the same
excitement we do.''
   Despite the rapid moves Soviet Bloc countries are making towards
democracy, the official said Cheney's overall message is to
``reaffirm the need for NATO.''
   He added the United States has pledged to maintain its financial
commitment to NATO through 1990. This comes as the Pentagon is
drawing up plans that would slash planned increases in U.S. defense
spending by $180 billion in the 1992-1994 budget years.
</TEXT>
