<FIRST>r a PM-FosterAttack     11-25 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foster Attack,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foster Mother of 10 Killed in Drug-Related Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A foster mother of 10 children was killed in
a gun battle between her son and four men that erupted over a
soured drug deal, police said.
   The foster children in the care of Elsie Jackson, 59, were
herded into a basement by relatives during the fight early Friday
and were not hurt. Mrs. Jackson's son, Darryl Ross, and another man
were injured, witnesses and police said.
   According to witnesses, the men broke into Mrs. Jackson's home
and confronted Ross during a family Thanksgiving party in the city
in northeastern Ohio.
   Ross, 25, and Moses Williams, 36, apparently shot each other,
the Stark County Sheriff's Department said.
   Williams will be charged with murder, said chief sheriff's
deputy Bruce Umpleby. Three other men will be charged with
complicity to aggravated burglary, he said.
   Mrs. Jackson was shot in the chest when she tried to persuade
Williams to leave the house, deputies said.
   Mrs. Jackson's daughter, Veronica Early, said the foster
children, ages 9 months to 16 years, were sleeping upstairs when
the shooting began. They awoke and came downstairs but were rushed
by relatives to safety in the basement, Ms. Early said.
   The children were placed in other foster homes by the county
Department of Human Services, the agency said.
</TEXT>
