<FIRST>r w PM-Obit-Lenihan     11-25 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Lenihan,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early Director of Navy's WAVES Dies.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired Navy Capt. Rita Lenihan, who served as
director of the women's part of the service from 1966 to 1971, has
died of cancer at the National Naval Medical Center in Bethesda, Md.
   Lenihan died Thursday at the age of 75.
   She joined the Navy in 1943, when WAVES, which stood for Women
Appointed for Voluntary Service, was still new.
   While serving as a newly commissioned ensign, Lenihan, who had
majored in Latin at the College of St. Elizabeth in Morristown,
N.J., wrote the motto for the coat of arms for WAVES officers:
``Honoris Est Nobis Navare Navales,'' which means ``It is an honor
for us to serve the fleet.''
   Lenihan, a native of Monroe, N.Y., spent most of her career in
Washington, although she also was stationed in Newport, R.I., and
in London.
   Her military decorations include the Legion of Merit.
   Survivors include a brother, Edward J. Lenihan of Verona, N.J.,
and a sister, Priscilla L. Lawler of Woodbridge, Conn.
</TEXT>
