<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     11-25 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shuttle Flight Continues in Secret, Astronauts Prepare for Sunday
Landing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The five Discovery astronauts
worked under a shroud of secrecy today while testing the shuttle's
control systems in preparation for a Sunday landing in the Mojave
Desert.
   A news blackout ordered by the military has prevented NASA from
talking about its classified mission, but sources said the crew's
main goal was to deploy a spy satellite.
   Discovery is scheduled to land Sunday at 7:02 p.m. PST at
Edwards Air Force Base, Calif. It will be the third after-dark
landing in 32 shuttle flights.
   While the Johnson Space Center has been mum about all aspects of
the mission since Thursday, it is assumed that the commander and
pilot Friday tested the shuttle's flight control systems and
steered thrusters to make sure they are ready for the trip back
home _ a fiery, hourlong dive through the Earth's atmosphere.
   Besides deploying a spy satellite, the Discovery astronauts
reportedly have been conducting experiments for the Strategic
Defense Initiative missile defense system. Neither NASA nor the
Pentagon would discuss the release of the satellite or other
mission objectives.
   The last official status report _ issued Thursday night by
Mission Control in Houston _ stated that the ``crew is doing well
and the orbiter continues to perform satisfactorily.''
   Sources close to the project said the astronauts had
accomplished their main goal of deploying a 2{-ton, $300 million
satellite capable of monitoring military and diplomatic
communications in the Soviet Union, the Middle East, Africa and
Europe.
   The Discovery mission is the fifth shuttle flight dedicated
solely to military research.
   Discovery is commanded by Air Force Col. Frederick D. Gregory.
The crew includes Air Force Col. John Blaha, the pilot, and three
mission specialists: Navy Capt. Manley Carter Jr., F. Story
Musgrave and Kathryn C. Thornton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
