<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HazelwoodHearing     11-25 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazelwood Hearing,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hazelwood Hearing to Begin Monday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The skipper of the Exxon Valdez will
try to get his case dismissed by claiming immunity from prosecution
and seeking to have the results of a sobriety test thrown out of
court.
   Joseph Hazelwood is expected to return to Alaska for a hearing
on the motions in the Anchorage Superior Court that begins Monday
and could last up to two weeks. His trial is set for Jan. 22.
   The 43-year-old mariner from Huntington, N.Y., was fired by
Exxon soon after the tanker Exxon Valdez struck a Prince William
Sound reef March 24 and spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil.
   The worst oil spill in U.S. history blackened pristine shores,
killed tens of thousands of birds and marine mammals and disrupted
lucrative fishing seasons. Exxon said it spent more than $1 billion
on oil spill claims and cleanup work, and state officials say the
cleanup still is not finished.
   Hazelwood faces misdemeanor charges of reckless endangerment,
operating a vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of
oil, and three felony counts of criminal mischief. If convicted of
the three felonies, he faces a possible maximum penalty of 10 years
in prison and $100,000 in fines.
   The case was moved from Valdez to Anchorage because of concerns
publicity about the spill would make it too hard to find an
impartial jury in Valdez. The southcentral Alaska port town relies
heavily on the oil industry for jobs and also has commercial
fishing interests.
   Defense motions include claims that Hazelwood received immunity
from prosecution when he reported his ship's grounding and oil
spill the morning it happened. A law designed to encourage
self-reporting of environmental calamities such as oil spills
provides protection against self-incrimination, laywers contend.
They say virtually every piece of evidence in the case against
Hazelwood grew from his report to the Coast Guard that the Exxon
Valdez was aground and leaking oil.
   State lawyers have pointed out that it would have been hard for
the massive oil spill to go undiscovered.
   Another defense motion asserts that the sobriety test Hazelwood
failed about 10 hours after the ship struck Bligh Reef was
administered improperly, and that the results cannot be used as
evidence.
   Defense lawyers say the sample was obtained so long after the
grounding that it did not provide a sound measure of Hazelwood's
condition at the time of the wreck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891125-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Church Bjt   11-25 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Church, Bjt,0938</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Puts Heat on Church After Rebel Offensive</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two commandos from the elite
Bracamonte Battalion materialize out of the shadows near a Jesuit
parish house.
   They stop a departing visitor.
   ``Who are you looking for?'' one demands coldly. ``What do you
want? Show me your identification.''
   The church is suspect in El Salvador, denounced by the right and
persecuted as subversive because it has become a force for social
change, a voice that denounces rights abuses.
   It threatens the status quo in a country where a handful are
wealthy and the majority live in ignorance, poverty and disease and
those who try to change things risk torture and death.
   It is also a country torn by a civil war pitting a leftist
guerrilla force against a succession of U.S.-backed governments _ a
war that has taken more than 71,000 lives.
   After the massacre of six Jesuit priests last week, Attorney
General Mauricio Colorado accused Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas
and auxiliary Bishop Gregorio Rosa Chavez of fomenting leftist
violence.
   He wrote to Pope John Paul II that the prelates should be pulled
out of El Salvador for their own good.
   The clerics, he said, have ``persisted in keeping alive the
questionable ideology of the `church of the poor''' and are blamed
for ``much of the violence that has devastated El Salvador for many
years and culminated in the rebel actions of this week ...''
   More than 1,000 people were killed in the 11-day offensive.
   A dozen years ago, a Jesuit activist, the Rev. Rutilio Grande,
asked what would happen if Jesus came to El Salvador.
   ``They'd accuse him of being a rebel, a foreign Jew, of getting
mixed up in exotic and strange ideas ... they'd crucify him,''
Grande said in a homily in the rural parish where he worked among
the poor.
   He was dead less than a month later, gunned down by a death
squad on his way to say Mass.
   Grande was one of the first priests to fall in the bloody
attempt to suppress church activism in El Salvador. Dozens of
priests, nuns and lay workers have been murdered since, including
the six Jesuit academics. Teachers, nurses, doctors, social
workers, academics _ all are suspect.
   Grande's life and death symbolized the new role for the Roman
Catholic Church in El Salvador.
   For hundreds of years, the church had worked with the Spanish
conquerors and colonial rulers and with the oligarchs that
followed. Ignore the misery of life on earth, it taught, and await
your celestial reward. There were few dissenting voices.
   In 1968, a Latin American bishop's conference in Medellin,
Colombia, decided the church should tend the material needs of the
poor as well as their spiritual needs, calling it a ``preferential
option for the poor.''
   Instead of counseling forbearance from the sidelines, many
clerics now felt their duties included standing at the side of
parishioners trying to do things such as organize peasant
cooperatives that might ease their crushing poverty.
   As war devastated El Salvador, the importance of churches and
church workers, both Catholic and Protestant, grew.
   Churches are virtually the only humanitarian institutions that
have continued to function throughout a decade of bitter civil war
between leftist guerrillas and a series of U.S.-backed governments.
   In a nation where political violence has fragmented families and
displaced hundreds of thousands, the only place to turn is often a
church. In some rural areas churches and church workers are the
only source of social services, health care and education as well
as spiritual nourishment.
   The church is also at the heart of the intellectual life of this
Massachusetts-sized nation of 5 million. The university where the
priests were massacred is one of the most respected institutions of
higher learning in Central America.
   El Salvador's right _ wealthy landowners and businessmen and
their military allies _ have raged at the sight of the church's
inherent power and influence standing shoulder-to-shoulder with
ideas they consider subversive.
   While the many in the churches blame the war on social and
economic factors, the right blames the conflict on those who try to
change them.
   ``The general feeling of the government is that all humanitarian
service groups in the country have sympathy for the rebels,'' the
Rev. Richard Potter, head of the Episcopal Church's partnership
officer for Latin America and the Caribbean, said in New York this
week after 19 layworkers at the Episcopal refugee center in San
Salvador were arrested.
   The country's only Episcopal pastor, the Rev. Luis Berrano
Laurente, was arrested the next day, Monday. The human rights
monitoring group America's Watch said Friday he was still in
custody.
   As the Salvadoran Roman Catholic church has supported its poor
parishioners, foreign priests, nuns, ministers, missionaries,
doctors, nurses, social worker and teachers have joined them.
   Episcopal, Lutheran, Baptist and Mennonite churches were on the
rosters of the dozens of churches, church schools, refuges and
social offices raided by authorities during the rebel offensive.
Americans, West Germans, Canadians, Spaniards and Guatemalans were
among those detained or deported.
   Many _ both Salvadorans and foreigners _ have fled, many have
gone into hiding in the past two weeks. But even so, they say the
work of the churches is not over.
   ``They feel needed here. And the more they are persecuted, the
more needed they feel,'' said an American academic with extensive
experience in El Salvador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
