<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RiotTrial     11-25 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Riot Trial,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer's Partner Defends Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A policeman on trial for two deaths that sparked a
race riot shot a motorcyclist in self-defense as he twisted to
avoid being hit by the vehicle, the officer's partner testified.
   Officer Dawn Campell said she was only a few feet behind William
Lozano the night of the Jan. 16 shooting. Lozano, 31, is Hispanic
and the two victims on the motorcycle were black.
   Prosecution witnesses had testified Ms. Campbell was on the
sidewalk and ducked down behind their patrol car at the moment of
the shooting.
   But on Friday she insisted she was in the middle of the street
when she heard sirens, then spotted the motorcycle speeding toward
Lozano at about 70 mph with another police car in pursuit.
   ``I saw the motorcycle come into the southbound lane, heading
straight for officer Lozano,'' she testified. ``As the motorcycle
got right up on him, I heard a `pop,' and saw officer Lozano give a
twisting movement.''
   She said the motorcycle passed within about a foot of Lozano,
who twisted to escape being hit.
   Prosecutors claim the motorcyclist did not threaten Lozano.
   The driver, Clement Lloyd, 23, died instantly with a bullet in
his head. His passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24, was critically
injured when the out-of-control motorcycle crashed. Blanchard died
the next day.
   Assistant State Attorney Don Horn asked if, despite departmental
rules, Ms. Campbell had talked to Lozano immediately after the
incident. She denied discussing the case and said she didn't recall
a conversation at the scene among her, Lozano, and a friend,
officer Manny Gonzalez.
   Horn then showed photographs of the three officers apparently
talking and making gestures just after the shooting. In one, Lozano
appeared to be standing in the position the defense says he
occupied at the time of the shooting, but Ms. Campbell denied they
were reenacting the scene. She and Lozano were together, she said,
because they had been ordered to find the spent shell casing.
   Prior to Ms. Campbell's testimony, defense attorney Roy Black
called the trial a political ploy.
   ``There is more effort made to prosecute a police officer than
any 10 murder cases I've ever seen in this court,'' he said.
   But lead prosecutor John Hogan responded he would make no
apology for the resources spent on the case.
   ``There is a large proportion of the people who live in Dade
County who feel that they could be killed, perhaps for absolutely
no reason because ... of the color of their skin,'' said Hogan.
``(And) because of the occupation of their killer, that no justice
will be done, that the justice system works only for the chosen
few.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
