<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern     11-25 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Say They'll Escalate Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines management and its Machinists
union agree on one thing _ the abrupt end of sympathy strikes by
the pilots and flight attendants won't immediately change the
airline's status.
   In anything, troubles were likely to be compounded for Eastern,
which said Friday it had no jobs to offer the returning pilots and
attendants. The Machinists vowed to continue and intensify their
8{-month strike despite the end of the sympathy walkouts.
   ``It really doesn't affect our operation at all,'' company
spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said. ``Now we have to deal with the
issue of bringing people back to work if there are openings.''
   The airline asked U.S. District Judge James L. King to determine
the status of all employees: those hired during the strike, union
members who crossed picket lines and returning strikers.
   ``We want to take care of that up front so everyone knows
clearly where they stand,'' Ms. Ceremsak said.
   A statement from the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers local said the other unions' action ``does not
have a material effect on the strike and on (Chairman Frank)
Lorenzo's failed reorganization plan. It does not change the
reality of Eastern's performance and the problems it faces in a
poor industry environment.''
   ``We're going to escalate the strike,'' said Frank Ortis,
president of Machinists Local 702. ``They're losing $2 million to
$3 million a day. We know they can't survive without maintenance.''
   The company is in disagreement with the pilots and flight
attendants unions on recalling former strikers, and Ortis noted
recent reports that cash-strapped Eastern has resumed negotiations
to sell its South American routes to American Airlines. Eastern
filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy laws five days after the strike began March 4.
   ``What are they going to do with those people if they sell South
America?'' Ortis said. He said hundreds of pilots and flight
attendants jobs are tied to those routes and Eastern would face
more legal fights about employees laid off after a sale.
   Although Ms. Ceremsak said Eastern was in solid shape on
maintenance, Machinists officials said Eastern's records declined
last month in on-time performance and customer complaints.
   According to Transportation Department figures released earlier
this month, Eastern's on-time performance fell to 80.6 percent in
September from 86.9 percent in August. Customer complaints fell to
7.93 per 100,000 passengers from 36.24 in August, but the figures
for both months were above the average of 5.77 per 100,000
passengers for the period from January to September.
   Ms. Ceremsak said Eastern has openings for 500 mechanics, with
2,500 on the current workforce including 300 Machinists who crossed
picket lines.
   She said Eastern has 1,700 union flight attendants who crossed
picket lines, and has hired 1,700 new flight attendants with
another 250 recruits in training. That gives the rebuilding carrier
all it needs, she said.
   Ms. Ceremsak said Eastern has 1,850 pilots, including 850 union
pilots who crossed picket lines and 1,000 new hirees, enough for
its schedule of 775 daily flights, which is scheduled to expand
gradually to more than 900 in early 1990.
   The returning strikers go on a recall list and will be called
back as openings come up, Ms. Ceremsak said. Eastern officials have
said seniority is less important than the pilots' qualifications
for specific planes and routes.
</TEXT>
