<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--WGermany-Iran     11-25 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--WGermany-Iran,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germany Company Under Investigation for Export to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEVERKUSEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are investigating
the giant chemical company Bayer AG on suspicion that it illegally
sold a pesticides plant to Iran, company officials said.
   West Germany has been rocked by several export scandals in the
past year. Some have involved allegations that West German
companies helped build a suspected chemical weapons plant in Libya.
   Many chemicals used to make pesticides can also be used in the
manufacture of chemical weapons.
   In its statement Friday, Bayer said customs officials suspect
its 1987 delivery of a pesticides plant to Iran violated West
Germany's export law.
   But the company said West German law does not require an export
permit for the kind of plant it sold to Iran for $2.7 million.
   Customs officials in Cologne refused to confirm that an
investigation was under way.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891125-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0341EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Korea-Defector     11-25 0113</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Korea-Defector,0115</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korean Soldier Defects to South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A North Korean soldier defected to
South Korea today by walking across the demilitarized zone that
forms the border between the two countries, the Defense Ministry
announced.
   The ministry said the soldier, identified as Kim Son-il, reached
a South Korean military outpost early today after crossing the
heavily fortified border about 40 miles northeast of Seoul.
   The defector was from the second platoon of the fifth company of
North Korea's 25th division, the ministry said. Ministry officials
provided no other details.
   So far this year, at least seven North Korean soldiers,
including Kim, have defected to South Korea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891125-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--ExplosivesFound     11-25 0126</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Explosives Found,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 10 People After Discovering Explosives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police found plastic explosives tucked into
cans of jam delivered by ship to the port city of Valencia. Ten
people were arrested.
   Police spokesman Manuel Jimenez said those arrested carried
passports of several nations, including Lebanon, and there was
suspicion they could be connected with a terrorist operation.
Lebanon is home to several terrorist groups.
   He said the investigation was in its initial stage after the
arrests were made Friday in Madrid and Valencia. The suspects were
being held in Madrid.
   He said police found 18 pounds of plastic explosives in the
first 100 jam cans they opened. He said a total of 1,600 cans had
arrived in Valencia by ship.
</TEXT>
