<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0417EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Czech-Milestones     11-25 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-Milestones,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Important Dates in Czechoslovak History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major dates in Czechoslovak
history:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 28, 1918 _ Czechoslovak state comes into existence upon the
dissolution of the Austrian-Hungary empire at the end of World War
I.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   March 1939 _ Nazi Germany incorporates Czech lands into the
Third Reich; German-sponsored Slovak government proclaims Slovakia
independent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 1945 _ Soviet Red Army and U.S. forces liberate
Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 20, 1948 _ Non-Communist ministers resign from
Communist-led coalition government to protest infiltration of
Communists into the police. Communists win majority in elections
two months later.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Aug. 21, 1968 _ Warsaw Pact forces invade Czechoslovakia to
crush the ``Prague Spring'' reform movement of Alexander Dubcek.
The government is forced to abandon most reforms and accept a
policy of ``normalization.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 16, 1969 _ Student Jan Palach immolates himself in
Wenceslas Square to protest the Soviet-led invasion, and he becomes
a symbol of resistance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 1, 1977 _ Human rights group Charter 77 is founded by
several hundred intellectuals, including playwright Vaclav Havel,
and former officials who signed a charter urging Czechoslovak
authorities to ensure the human rights guaranteed in the Helsinki
Accords.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dec. 17, 1987 _ Communist Party chief Gustav Husak is replaced
by Politburo member Milos Jakes, who oversaw the expulsion from the
party of more than 450,000 members loyal to Dubcek.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nov. 24, 1989 _ Ruling Communist Party Politburo and Secretariat
resign, forced out by a growing pro-democracy movement that had
filled the streets with hundreds of thousands of protesters.
Little-known Karel Urbanek replaces Milos Jakes as party leader.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
