<DOCNO> AP891125-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0418EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Massacre-Witness     11-25 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Massacre-Witness,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness To Shooting of Jesuit Priests in San Salvador in Hiding in
Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who witnessed the massacre of six Jesuit
priests in El Salvador last was spirited to the United States by
Spanish, French and U.S. diplomats and is under guard here at a
secret location.
   The witness was flown Thursday night to Miami from San Salvador
aboard a French military plane with the assistance of a key French
official, the Miami Herald reported in today's editions.
   She has been identified as Lucia Barrera Cerna, 40, a cleaning
woman who worked for two of the slain priests at Jose Simeon Canas
Central American University.
   According to unidentified officials cited by the Herald, the
woman saw the priests and two university employees shot at
point-blank range on Nov. 16 by a group of 30 to 40 men wearing
Salvadoran military uniforms.
   Her account appeared to bolster charges by church officials and
others that the killings were carried out by members of the
Salvadoran military. Salvadoran officials have claimed the killings
could have been the work of leftists trying to pass themselves off
as Salvadoran soldiers.
   The witness also was interviewed by Salvadoran officials, and
Salvadoran Attorney General Mauricio Eduardo Colorado was quoted in
the Herald as saying the witness saw just five assasins _ three
dressed in black and two in olive-green uniforms.
   Bernard Kouchner, the French minister for humanitarian affairs,
said he escorted the woman, her husband and their daughter to the
United States. Kouchner said the family has been handed over to the
U.S. State Department for protection.
   But other, unidentified officials involved in the case said the
witness and her family were being guarded by the FBI. A spokeswoman
at the Miami office of the FBI refused to confirm or deny the
report.
   Kouchner said he was in San Salvador last weekend to attend the
funerals of the priests, and learned Wednesday the witness and her
family were in the Spanish Embassy and wanted to go to Miami.
   ``Inside Salvador it was impossible to protect them,'' Kouchner
said. ``There were death squadrons all around.''
   Kouchner said he offered France's assistance in bringing the
family to Miami, and was joined on the trip by two unidentified
U.S. diplomats, and bodyguards.
   ``We transferred the lady (to San Salvador's airport) under the
protection of our bodyguards and security people from the French
and Spanish embassies,'' Kouchner said, adding that the U.S.
ambassador to El Salvador, William Walker, was present.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani approved of the witness'
relocation to the United States, Kouchner said.
   Meanwhile, an American priest who fled El Salvador last week
after receiving death threats said he planned to carry out a
campaign to end U.S. aid to Cristiani's rightist government.
   The Rev. Jim Barnett, visiting St. Paul, Minn., this week, said
that during heavy fighting in the Salvadoran capital last week he
called friends in the United States to say that the government was
hurting civilians by bombing and strafing of poor neighborhoods
where leftist rebels were entrenched.
   Barnett said he then received a telephoned death threat at the
residence for Catholic and Lutheran clerics where he lived, and
decided to leave the country.
   Many clergy in El Salvador have been threatened by rightists
since the guerrilla offensive began two weeks ago. Many priests are
in hiding. Church members often are accused of sheltering or
supplying the rebels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891125-0039 </DOCNO>
