<HEAD>Winter Storm Develops Over West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cloudy skies prevailed over much of the nation early today,
while a winter storm developed over the West.
   A storm watch has been posted for the northern Sierra Nevada
range of California with more than 2 feet of snow possible in some
of the higher elevations.
   A winter storm watch also has been issued for the mountains of
southern Idaho for tonight and Sunday.
   Showers dampened much of the northern and central Pacific Coast
region Friday. In western Oregon, a thunderstorm north of Newport
produced hail a half-inch in diameter and wind gusts to 50 mph.
   A cold front brought snow to parts of Utah, Wyoming and Colorado.
   An advisory for snow and blowing snow is in effect today for the
northern and central mountains of Colorado, with 4 to 8 inches
expected.
   A snow advisory also was in effect for the mountains of western
Wyoming, where 4 to 8 inches of new snow were expected.
   Snow squalls continued over parts of the lower Great Lakes
region Friday evening. Snow squalls over western New York produced
7 inches of snow west of Amboy. A 60-car accident forced the
closure of Route 81 Friday afternoon.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms dampened extreme southern
Florida.
   High temperatures were only in the 20s and 30s Friday across
much of the area from the northern half of the Atlantic Coast
through the Great Lakes region into eastern sections of the Dakotas.
   Record lows for the date were set or tied in 12 Northeast cities
Friday. Temperatures dropped to 1 degree in Hartford, Conn., and
Caribou, Maine.
   The high for the nation Friday was 80 degrees in Arizona at
Tucson and Yuma.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST:
