<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0437EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CubsLawsuit     11-25 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cubs Lawsuit,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Indiana Boy $67,000 For Foul Ball Injury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has ordered the Chicago Cubs to pay
$67,500 in damages to a boy who was struck in the eye by a foul
ball during a game at Wrigley Field, attorneys said.
   The award to Delbert Yates Jr., 16, is only the second of its
kind in the country, Cubs lawyer William Cremer said. In the other
case, a lawsuit against the Houston Astros, the verdict was
reversed on appeal, and Cremer said the Cubs would appeal.
   Contacted Friday night at the family's Valparaiso, Ind., home,
the boy's father, Delbert Sr., said, ``We're pretty happy ...
because maybe the Cubs will do something to protect the fans now.''
   The younger Yates was struck in the face by a foul ball off the
bat of Cubs slugger Leon Durham during an Aug. 20, 1983, game
against Atlanta. He was sitting in a box seat on the third base
side of home plate just a few feet from the protective screen.
   The boy was treated at a ballpark first aid station and taken by
ambulance to a children's hospital, where he spent five days. He
suffered a fractured eye socket which caused double vision, and
required an eye operation a month later, said his lawyer, Mario
Cirignani.
   Cirignani had contended that the protective screen behind home
plate should have been extended further. He said a Cook County
Circuit Court jury on Wednesday awarded Yates $67,500 for his pain
and suffering.
   But Cremer said, ``I think there is an excellent chance of
getting it reversed.''
   ``If the verdict is upheld, what do the Cubs do?'' Cremer asked.
``Do they then screen the entire park to protect themselves against
liability? Catching foul balls is as much a part of baseball as
crackerjacks and peanuts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
