<FIRST>r a PM-SFQuake-SantaCruz     11-25 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SF Quake-Santa Cruz,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Businesses Reopen in Santa Cruz _ in Tents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Holiday Shopping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 45 businesses displaced by the
Oct. 17 earthquake reopened in temporary quarters _ seven huge
tents erected just in time to attract holiday shoppers.
   ``We love Santa Cruz and this is part of our life,'' said Louise
Bagnall, a shopper in the tent pavilion, which was erected on the
site of the Pacific Garden Mall, devastated in the 7.1-magnitude
quake. ``We just felt we must support Santa Cruz and see it come
out of the rubble and live again.''
   A ribbon was cut to open the shopping pavilion to business
Friday and ``within minutes the place was packed,'' said Louis
Rittenhouse, president of the Downtown Association.
   ``We hope people will return to Santa Cruz to shop and spend
long weekends now,'' Mayor Mardi Wormhoudt said in a statement.
   Many of the small to medium-sized businesses feared they would
go out of business if they were not open in time for the holiday
shopping season.
   Some store owners relied on the kindness of strangers to get
their businesses going in the tents.
   Margaret Wilson, owner of Lilly Wong's gift store, said she was
able to set up shop in three days thanks to about 30 volunteers who
helped each day.
   ``Those were people I'd never even seen before,'' she said.
</TEXT>
