<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TexasCzechs     11-25 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Czechs,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czech Immigrants in Central Texas Community Watching Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week ago, the editor of a Czech-language
newspaper published in this tiny, central Texas town predicted in a
column that change would soon come to his homeland.
   But Jan Vaculik, who left Czechoslovakia a month after the
Soviet invasion in 1968, was stunned when the hard-line members of
the Czechoslovak Politburo resigned Friday.
   ``I didn't expect such change so rapidly,'' Vaculik said. ``I'm
excited at least that these guys are gone. I always feared that
they may turn violent against the people.''
   Vaculik, 44, publishes the monthly Hospodar for 1,000
subscribers in the United States and 1,000 in Czechoslovakia, he
said. Most of the paper's readers are older and remember the
``dream of the First Republic,'' the only independent
Czechoslovakian republic, from 1918 to 1938.
   ``They know there is a different way,'' Vaculik said.
   About 85 percent of West's 2,300 residents are of Czechoslovak
descent, Vaculik said, but only a handful were born in
Czechoslovakia. Good farming conditions and cheap land brought most
of them to West in the 1870s.
   The town's 22-member dance ensemble toured Czechoslovakia last
year.
   ``It was really a culture shock. Things that we have at our
fingertips they're not able to have,'' said Maggie Grmela, who
started the dance group with her husband 14 years ago. ``We're
pleased to see what's happening now.'' In Granger, a town about 80
miles south of West that is also predominantly Czech, residents are
also watching events in Czechoslovakia closely. Both towns are in
central Texas between Dallas and San Antonio.
   ``It looks like they might finally get some freedom, but it's
hard to judge,'' said Jannine Lalla, who visited Czechoslovakia 11
years ago. ``They're a complicated outfit over there. The people
are so nice, but they are afraid.''
   Joe Vrabel of Granger publishes Nasinec, a 75-year old
Czech-language weekly newspaper, but has never been able to sell
the paper in Czechslovakia. He hopes the changes pro-democracy
demonstrators seek will enable him to do so.
   ``I never thought it would be free there again,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
