<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel 4thLd-Writethru a0473 11-25 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0473,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Planes Raid Bekaa Valley in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with raids seen as Israeli warning to
Syria, change casualties to fatalities in 5th graf, UPDATE penultimate
graf with latest number of attacks, wounded. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHTOURA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today blasted a
guerrilla base of a radical Palestinian faction near Syrian army
lines in southeast Lebanon. At least two group members were
wounded, police said.
   In Israel, an army spokesman confirmed the air attack on Sultan
Yaaqoub, the second on the village in three days. The jets returned
safely to base.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing rules,
said the strike was aimed at ``terrorist targets related to Ahmed
Jibril.''
   Jibril is a former Syrian army captain who heads the radical
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command.
   A Lebanese police spokesman confirmed that the target was a
Popular Front base. There were no immediate reports of fatalities.
   The police spokesman said two fighter-bombers fired six rockets
into the base in Sultan Yaaqoub, in the Bekaa Valley, in two late
morning runs.
   The spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said the planes also
dropped about six time bombs that exploded in a 10-minute period
after the air attack.
   Syrian soldiers manning surface-to-air missile batteries in the
Bekaa Valley did not fire at the raiding jets, the spokesman said.
   Witnesses said guerrilla defenders fired on the attacking jets
with twin-barreled, anti-aircraft guns, but no hits were observed.
   They said smoke billowed from a one-story building at the base
seconds after rockets crashed into it.
   The air raids today and Thursday were seen as a warning to Syria
to prevent its guerrilla allies from taking advantage of the
current political turmoil in Lebanon to stage attacks on Israel.
   Both raids followed the assassination of Lebanese President Rene
Mouawad. Today's bombing came hours after the election of a
presidential successor, Elias Hrawi, a Maronite Catholic also
backed by the Syrians.
   On Thursday, four Israeli F-4 Phantom fighter-bombers struck
bases of the Syrian-backed Popular Front in Sultan Yaaqoub and the
adjacent Deir Zanoun in a 10-minute attack. One fighter was killed
and four were wounded.
   The pro-Iranian fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God, also
has bases in the area. Hezbollah is the umbrella group for Shiite
Moslem factions holding 18 Western hostages in Lebanon, including
eight Americans.
   Today's raid was Israel's 16th attack on targets in Lebanon this
year. By police count, the raids have killed 18 people and wounded
109.
   The Popular Front is opposed to peace overtures by Palestine
Liberation Organization chairman Yasser Arafat.
</TEXT>
