<FIRST>u i PM-India-Elections 2ndLd-Writethru   11-25 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0460,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote Fraud Found in Gandhi's District</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE death toll, ADD report of vote fraud in
Gandhi's district, interview with opposition leader. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campaign workers fought pitched battles
in India's biggest city today, and the Election Commission
announced there was evidence of vote rigging in Prime Minister
Rajiv Gandhi's district.
   A respected weekly released a poll saying Gandhi's party will be
``hard pressed'' to win 200 seats in the 543-seat Lok Sabha, or
House of the People, Parliament's decision-making lower chamber
which will choose the prime minister. The poll in Sunday magazine
interviewed 11,500 voters.
   In another development, opposition leader Vishwanath Pratap
Singh, considered the top choice to replace Gandhi, said he was
reluctant to become prime minister should his five-party opposition
coalition win.
   ``It is political suicide to depend too much on an individual,''
Singh said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``So I have
decided not to accept any proposal to become the prime minister.''
   Violence continued today when campaign workers in Calcutta, the
capital of West Bengal, battled with bombs and bricks.
   One election official was killed and dozens were injured. Police
fired into the air and used tear gas to disperse the crowds.
   Two other people were killed in campaign-related violance, one
in southern Andhra Pradesh and the other in southern Tamil Nadu.
   So far 97 people have died since voting began Wednesday.
   The elections, which end Sunday and will determine whether
Gandhi remains in power or falls victim to a newly energized and
united opposition, are shaping up as the most violent in India's
history.
   At least 141 people have been killed since the election was
announced in mid-October, surpassing the 38 people who died during
the December 1984 election that propelled Gandhi to power two
months after the assassination of his mother, Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi.
   Voting will take place Sunday in tiny Sikkim, the northern state
of Punjab where Sikh separatists have killed more than 1,650 people
this year, and in eastern Bihar state where violence between Hindus
and Moslems has left at least 300 people dead in the past six weeks.
   First election results are expected Sunday night after the polls
close.
   Since the voting started, the Congress Party and the opposition
National Front coalition have traded charges of voter intimidation
and ballot fraud.
   Chief Election Commissioner R.V.S. Peri Sastri said an
investigation in Gandhi's district has found evidence of vote
rigging in 50 percent of the polling places it checked.
   The Congress Party has denied it was responsible for rigging in
Amethi, the constituency where Gandhi is seeking re-election.
   Peri Sastri said he hoped a decision would be made on a revote
in the Amethi district Sunday when counting is supposed to begin.
   Revoting has already been ordered in 930 of the country's
590,000 polling places because of ballot fraud.
   Peri Sastri's dramatic news conference began when 40 Indian
reporters barged into his office. Soon afterward he received a
telephone call from an Election Commission investigator who had
been sent to Gandhi's district to investigate allegations of vote
fraud.
   Peri Sastri allowed reporters to stay in the room as he spoke
with the investigator, C.L. Rose.
   Rose visited 35 polling stations in 10 villages and reported
rigging in 50 percent of them, Peri Sastri said. Villagers issued
``angry and grievious complaints against the voting,'' Peri Sastri
said. He said the decision on Amethi was a serious one.
   ``Here is an allegation which will damage not merely an
individual but an institution, the institution is the prime
ministership,'' he said.
   He said his decision would not just effect the district but the
``whole country as well.''
   The Congress Party has been accused of large-scale rigging in
Amethi.
</TEXT>
