<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0463,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Hold 10 Passengers For Questioning About Airplane Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with airline saying 339 people aboard,
ransom demanded, police questioning 10 passengers. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today questioned 10 passengers
about a bomb found aboard a Saudi jumbo jet carrying 339 people.
The bomb failed to go off, and the plane returned to Pakistan
safely.
   The Boeing 747 was traveling from Islamabad to Riyadh, Saudi
Arabia. Saudi Arabian Airlines Flight 367 was flying over the
Arabian Sea when it was ordered to land in the southern port city
of Karachi because of an extortion threat.
   While the plane was airborne, officials said airport security in
Islamabad received an anonymous letter threatening to blow the
plane up unless a demand for $15 million was met.
   In Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, the airline today issued a statement
saying that ``with God's blessing,'' a bomb found in a piece of
unclaimed luggage failed to go off, sparing the lives of the 332
adults and seven children aboard.
   Eight ounces of dynamite were found in the unclaimed bag, said
Moinuddin, the head of a bomb squad. The dynamite was surrounded by
clothes, a cigarette lighter and a box of matches, said Moinuddin,
who only uses one name.
   Earlier police reports called the device a time bomb and said
only a loose battery wire prevented it from exploding.
   Police gave few details about the 10 passengers held for
questioning. ``We haven't laid any charges; we are just questioning
them,'' said a Karachi police official on condition of anonymity.
   He said all 10 were from Pakistan's North West Frontier Province.
   Islamabad police said they also were questioning a taxi driver
who delivered the extortion letter to an Islamabad airport officer
shortly after Flight 367 left Islamabad.
   The note demanded $15 million in ransom to be deposited in three
bags at a location in Islamabad, said the Saudi airline. Pakistani
police earlier put the figure at $1.5 million.
   No one has claimed responsibility for placing the bomb on the
plane, and police have refused to discuss possible suspects.
   A terrorist bomb exploded aboard a New York-bound Pan Am jumbo
jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988, killing all 259
people aboard and 11 people on the ground. Investigators in England
later determined that the explosion was caused by a bomb hidden in
a cassette-recorder.
</TEXT>
