<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     11-25 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Vietnamese Battle at Detention Center; Police Fire Tear
Gas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today fired tear gas into a refugee camp
to break up a battle between hundreds of Vietnamese boat people
armed with stones and spears, officials said. At least five people
were injured.
   The fight between rival groups from two different provinces in
Vietnam broke out after a man was attacked, police said. The
Vietnamese tore down a 17-foot-tall fence that separated the two
groups at the Shek Kong center.
   Police reported four Vietnamese were injured, including a man
who was hospitalized in fair condition with stab wounds to the
chest. A police officer was also slightly injured but required no
hospital treatment.
   Besides using stones and spears, the boat people also fought
with water pipes and sharpened iron rods before police dispersed
them, officials said.
   There have been frequent fights in recent months among
Vietnamese boat people held in detention camps in this small
British colony.
   More than 55,000 Vietnamese refugees are languishing in the Hong
Kong camps, hoping for resettlement and fearing forced repatriation
to their Communist-ruled homeland.
   It is expected that tens of thousands of boat people will be
denied refugee status by Hong Kong, and tension has increased in
the camps with the possibility that they will be sent back to
Vietnam.
   On Friday, British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said his
country has ``little choice'' except compulsory repatriation for
the boat people, who are putting an ``intolerable strain on Hong
Kong's patience and resources.''
   At a Camp David meeting Friday, President Bush criticized
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher for the plan to force the
boat people back to Vietnam. Mrs. Thatcher made no comment on the
criticism when she returned to Britain today, but a Foreign Office
official, William Waldegrave, said:
   ``What are we supposed to do? They cannot just sit there in
those camps getting cholera. We have to do something. I do not know
what else there is to do. Everyone shares the anxiety.
   ``We have tried to persuade the international community to take
them. The international community will not take them _ not America,
not Sweden, not Switzerland, Australia, not anybody.''
</TEXT>
