<FIRST>r a PM-LooseBombs 1stLd-Writethru a0456 11-25 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loose Bombs, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0456,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Steps Up Cleanup of Live and Dead Bombs on Nevada Public Lands</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to RECAST, clarifying that cleanup resuming,
sted beginning. Picks up 7th graf, `Please know...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy, under pressure from state officials
worried about safety, has stepped up plans to retrieve live and
deactivated explosives accidently dropped onto public lands outside
bombing ranges.
   The Navy will start looking for the loose ordnance on Bureau of
Land Management property outside two of its bombing ranges during
the next three weeks, said Capt. Rex Rackowitz, commanding officer
of the Fallon Naval Air Station.
   The search is a continuation of an exercise nicknamed
``Operation Ugly Baby'' to retrieve stray bombs that have dotted
the desert at least 60 miles outside Reno for up to 30 years.
   No accidents have been reported involving the bombs, but state
officials have been outraged since revelations surfaced that the
Navy in October began a secret operation outside its Bravo 17 range
to retrieve errant explosives.
   The Navy said it was secretive to prevent the curious from
collecting souvenirs or interfering in the cleanup.
   Navy officials had planned to start the cleanup around two other
bombing rantes, Bravo 16 and Bravo 19, in the spring. In a letter
to Gov. Bob Miller on Friday, Rackowitz said the work would resume
now in order to better protect the public and quickly resolve the
situation that has drawn the unwanted attention of state
environmental officials.
   ``Please know that the Navy is attempting to resolve this
situation quickly and with utmost concern for the safety of the
citizens and property of Nevada,'' Rackowitz wrote.
   Nevada Environmental Protection Chief Lew Dodgion this week
cited the Navy for violating state law by leaving bombs on public
lands. He said he might seek fines as high as $10,000 a day against
the Navy for failing to notify the state about the hazardous
materials cleanup, and failing to file a plan for the recovery
operation.
   Rackowitz said some of the bombs and rockets may have landed
outside the fenced ranges because of inexperienced pilots or
equipment failure.
   The bureau has closed off lands around the ranges during the
cleanup.
   The Navy plans to sweep for bombs outside its Bravo 16 bombing
range beginning Monday through Dec. 2 and on Bravo 19 from Dec.
4-15. About 150 naval personnel are traveling to Fallon to help.
   More than 80,000 pounds of scrap metal and bombs were recovered
from more than 2,000 pieces of ordnance during the the Bravo 17
cleanup, the Navy said.
</TEXT>
