<FIRST>r a AM-Fulton-Wall     11-25 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fulton-Wall,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Move To Show Berlin Wall Where Churchill Cited Iron Curtain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT CHARTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winston Churchill made his historic speech
about an ``iron curtain'' across Europe in this college town 43
years ago. Now, there's a move to pay tribute to the disintegration
of that curtain by putting part of the broken Berlin Wall on
permanent display.
   Supporters of the idea say it would be a tangible tribute to
Churchill's descriptive phrase, delivered in a lecture at
Westminster College here 43 years ago.
   Diplomatic, logistic and financial barriers would have to be
crossed. Still, supporters say Westminster is the right place for a
symbol of chilled East-West relations.
   ``This was where Winston Churchill first used those words about
an `iron curtain' descending across Eastern Europe. The first
glimpse in 1989 of that curtain ascending across Eastern Europe
brings us a sense of closure to his prediction,'' says the Rev.
Michael Vaughn, pastor of First Presbyterian Church in Fulton.
   ``I would like to see the memorial here which notes Churchill's
moment in history bracketed with the other end of history: the fall
of the Berlin Wall.''
   Out of government, but with a wartime leader's perspective on
postwar Europe, Churchill spoke at Westminster on March 5, 1946.
Introduced by President Harry S. Truman, the former prime minister
called for unity between Great Britain and the United States.
   Then he uttered these famous words:
   ``From Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste in the Adriatic an iron
curtain has descended across the Continent.
   ``Behind that line lie all the capitals of the ancient states of
Central and Eastern Europe _ Warsaw, Berlin, Prague, Vienna,
Budapest, Belgrade, Bucharest and Sofia.
   ``All these famous cities and the populations around them lie in
what I must call the Soviet sphere, and all are subject in one form
or another, not only to Soviet influence but a very high and, in
many cases, increasing measure of control from Moscow.''
   Churchill, who died in 1965, is memorialized at the school with
a towering statue, an extensive archive and museum, and in an
ancient stone church that was moved from London after being blasted
by German bombs.
   Visitors say the rebuilt church is proof of a future after
conflict, and Vaughn says the relocated wall could also be
inspiring.
   ``I think part of the symbolism should be a massive gap in the
wall if it's brought here _ like the cross, which was a sign of
execution, that we now lift up as a sign of hope in Christianity,''
he says.
   ``Now, a wall that separated us has cracked and come down and
shown us that physical barriers cannot divide free people.''
   East Germany's opening of its border to the West prompted
celebrations at Westminster, where students and townspeople packed
the old church on a recent evening for a service of thanksgiving.
   ``We are here to celebrate the death of an inanimate object _ a
wall,'' Jack Rogers, head of Ecumenical Ministries of Callaway
County, told the worshipers. ``Yet that wall has come to symbolize
all that has kept us apart.''
   For Vaughn, moving a section of the Berlin Wall to Fulton would
be a way of bringing people together.
   ``Often the people of Israel would erect stones to momentous
events, often as altars but sometimes just groups of stones. Later
their children would ask them, `What mean these stones?'
   ``When later generations come, we can point to these stones, if
you will, from the Berlin Wall and say, `This is a period in our
life when we learned how to make peace.'''
</TEXT>
