<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1249EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-D'Amato     11-25 1160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-D'Amato,990</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bad Days for Senator Pothole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The day after the Village Voice ran a story
alleging he'd made phone calls to a federal prosecutor on behalf of
two mobsters, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato was acting punchy.
   The report was one more in a series of blows the press has
landed on New York's pugnacious Republican senator, and he returned
a phone call to put his spin on what had happened. But instead of
his usual, ``Howahyah?'' greeting, the senator burst into an
off-key ditty, based loosely on Allan Sherman's parody about an
unhappy camper, ``Hello Mudda, Hello Fadda.''
   ``This is Alfonse.
   ``I've had better
   ``Times and days. ...''
   To the suggestion that things couldn't be that bad, D'Amato was
inspired to a second verse:
   ``The singing waiter
   ``In the future.
   ``How you like your
   ``Wine and pasta?''
   He dissolved into asthmatic laughter. Had Al D'Amato finally
lost it?
   Not at all. Songs and silliness, pet names and baby talk _ this
is D'Amato behind the scenes, schmoozing, cajoling, disarming,
playing the affable dope. And right now, D'Amato needs all the
friends he can get.
   Just as ``Senator Pothole'' had begun to shed his image as a
world-class pork-barreler and small-town machine pol, the media
uncovered his remarkable ability to manipulate the federal
Department of Housing and Urban Development to the benefit of his
campaign contributors and friends.
   And he has other troubles. The Village Voice recounted two
questionable phone calls that the senator made to then-U.S.
Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in 1984 and '85. The Voice said the calls
were on behalf of mobsters; D'Amato denies it.
   Another recent charge involved D'Amato's brother, Armand, a
former state assemblyman who is now a lawyer in private practice.
Armand obtained information for Unisys Corp. by drafting a letter
to the Navy in his brother's name regarding a $100 million
antimissile contract. Unisys was a $35,000-a-year client of Armand
D'Amato's law firm.
   Sen. D'Amato said he was unaware that his brother represented
the Long Island contractor, and said he also had not known about
the letter.
   Since last spring, each week has seemed to bring a new
allegation against D'Amato, and the charges are taking a political
toll. Two recent polls _ one statewide, the other in New York City
_ showed D'Amato's popularity declining for the first time since he
was elected in 1980. In July, Mark Green, the Democrat who lost to
D'Amato in 1986, asked the Senate Select Committee on Ethics to
investigate.
   On Nov. 17, the ethics committee hired Robert S. Bennett as a
special counsel to determine whether an investigation of alleged
influence-peddling is warranted.
   In an interview last week, D'Amato said he is the victim of a
``pile on'' by the press, adding that he was certain the ethics
inquiry will exonerate him.
   ``I'm proud of my record,'' he said. ``I have nothing to be
ashamed of.''
   D'Amato said his support for housing projects has had nothing to
do with whether a particular developer or applicant had supported
him politically.
   ``Show me where there is a situation where there has been a
town, where there has been a county, where there has been a
worthwhile program or project that has asked for our support where
we've ever turned them aside,'' he challenged.
   And he predicted he will be just the first senator to undergo
similar scrutiny.
   ``If you were to ask for all the letters that various
congressmen and senators sent on behalf of constituents (to) HUD,
you will find that there are a number of grants that have been
successful and that people contributed to them,'' he said.
   ``Are we going to say, therefore, people should be precluded who
contribute to your campaign from normal constituent services? I'm
not talking about things which are extraordinary or things that are
wrong. But a letter of support of a letter of inquiry to take a
look at something? I don't think that's the case.''
   D'Amato's image began to erode in May when the Wall Street
Journal reported how the Reagan-era HUD favored well-heeled
developers who contributed generously to the GOP and hired powerful
Washington consultants.
   Around HUD, the story said, D'Amato was known as ``the senator
from Puerto Rico'' because of the keen interest he took in helping
the commonwealth win subsidies. Some Puerto Rican developers who
obtained these funds were big contributors to D'Amato's re-election
campaigns.
   D'Amato has since denied that he had ever tried to steer HUD
money to any particular developer in Puerto Rico.
   The New York Times dealt D'Amato a second blow two weeks later,
when it reported on irregularities in how inexpensive HUD houses
were awarded in the early 1980s in D'Amato's hometown of Island
Park, N.Y.
   D'Amato has said he played no role in his cousin getting a house
and he has praised the Island Park HUD program.
   But the Times story also chronicled the tale of Island Park's
pork barrel pool, which was to be built using a $425,000 grant
D'Amato had wheedled out of a special fund controlled by then-HUD
Secretary Samuel Pierce. In July, the village dropped the project
after unfavorable news reports.
   How does D'Amato justify asking HUD to build a swimming pool in
a middle-class, beach front community, when so many Americans are
homeless?
   ``It was a grievous error in political judgment,'' he admitted
last week. `... If you want to say I was naive as it relates to
Island Park, I was. Dumb.''
   Throughout the summer, as HUD released reams of old files and a
House panel conducted investigative hearings, D'Amato's name came
up again and again. Sometimes his name was being used without his
permission, says D'Amato.
   D'Amato came from Long Island politics to win election to the
Senate after a challenge to Sen. Jacob Javits, R-N.Y., in which he
capitalized on Javits' age (76), illness (a progressive nerve
disease) and liberalism.
   In his first term, D'Amato earned a reputation as the senator
who got the little things done for New York. He bucked his own
party by fighting against President Reagan's demand for an end to
federal subsidies that help pay for mass transit systems, and he
defended tax-exempt industrial development bonds as a stimulus for
creating and retaining thousands of jobs in New York.
   During his second term, D'Amato perfected his knack for latching
instantly onto issues of great public relations value, and emitting
much sound and fury.
   ``As a senator, D'Amato has also been shrewd to the point of
shamelessness in taking practically any position, espousing any
cause, and lobbying for any project or program that could be
popular with even the smallest segment of the New York
electorate...,'' observed ``The Almanac of American Politics 1990.''
   Still, Norman Ornstein, a scholar with the American Enterprise
Institute in Washington, said in a recent interview that he
believed D'Amato had been on his way to winning some respect as a
senator _ until HUD.
</TEXT>
