<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Uruguay     11-25 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Party Favored To Win South American Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition party that has won only
two national elections this century is favored to defeat the
governing Colorado Party in balloting Sunday.
   The vote follows a lackluster campaign that brought out few
differences between the Colorados and the opposition National Party
or their main candidates _ one the son and great-nephew of
presidents; the other the grandson of a longtime party leader.
   Neither center-right party severely criticized the other,
alleged campaign violations or indicated they would dispute the
outcome.
   The winning candidate will replace President Jorge Sanguinetti,
who took over from a 12-year military dictatorship in 1985. The
change of political leadership was not expected to bring major
shifts in policy.
   Polls gave Luis Lacalle of the National Party a big edge over
the main Colorado candidate, Jorge Batlle, whose name is pronounced
BAHT-lee. Equipos Consultores, the country's most respected polling
agency, projected the Nationals would receive 38 percent of the
total vote and the Colorados 30 percent.
   Lacalle and Batlle cite the same problems _ inflation, low
growth, high foreign debt payments, deteriorating public services.
Both want to cut government bureaucracy, allow private companies to
compete with state firms in some areas, sell gold reserves to
reduce the debt and reform public education.
   The Colorados and the Nationals have dominated political power
for a century and a half, except during the 1973-85 military
dictatorship.
   Political observers said Lacalle, whose campaign was considered
a long shot when he started 18 months ago, overtook Batlle by
convincing voters he was less ideological and would undertake
reforms through consensus.
   ``Lacalle has not said exactly what he'll do, but it looks like
he'll do it by coalition, not by force,'' said Luis Rosadilla, a
former Tupamaro guerrilla whose political wing, the Movement for
Popular Participation, supports the leftist Broad Front candidate
for president, Liber Seregni.
   A favorite Lacalle remark is, ``I want to be a president
respected by everyone and feared by no one.''
   Lacalle, 48, is an attorney and was first elected a national
deputy in 1971. During the dictatorship, which followed an attempt
by left-wing terrorists to overthrow the government, he worked on
the family ranch in central Uruguay and practiced law.
   The grandson of Luis Alberto de Herrera, the National Party's
leader for five decades until his death in 1959, Lacalle was
elected to the Senate in 1984.
   Batlle, 62, also an attorney and senator, is the great-nephew of
former President Jose Batlle y Ordonez, who set up Uruguay's
welfare state at the turn of the century. His father, President
Luis Batlle, extended those reforms following World War II.
   Twelve candidates are running for president, although only
Lacalle and Batlle, and perhaps former president Jorge Pacheco
Areco, another Colorado candidate, have a real chance at victory.
   A party may field several candidates. The Colorados and
Nationals have three each. Thus, Lacalle will win if the votes cast
for the three National presidential candidates exceed the total
number of votes cast for any other party.
   Sanguinetti is barred by law from seeking immediate re-election.
   Also at stake is the makeup of the 30-member Senate and
99-member House of Deputies as well as governments in 19 provinces.
   Polls open at 8 a.m. and close at 7:30 p.m. Preliminary tallies
are expected late Sunday.
   Voting is mandatory for Uruguayans 18 years and older. Failure
to vote is punishable by a small fine.
   The National Party ruled this nation of 2.9 million between
Brazil and Argentina from 1959-67, winning elections in 1958 and
1962. The term of office later was expanded to five years.
Sanguinetti is due to step down in March 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
