<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0510,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Jets Hit Guerrillas with Rockets, Delayed-Action Bombs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 6th, `The delayed...' with Israeli no
comment, pvs reports of use of such bombs; picks up 7th pvs, `Syrian soldiers...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHTOURA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes attacked a Palestinian
guerrilla base for the second time in three days Saturday, and
Lebanese police said the jets dropped time bombs that exploded as
rescuers dug through the rubble.
   At least two guerrillas of the Syrian-backed Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine-General Command base were wounded in
the air raid, police said.
   In Israel, an army spokesman confirmed the attack on the
guerrilla base. He said the jets returned safely.
   A Lebanese police spokesman said two fighter-bombers fired six
rockets into the base in Sultan Yaaqoub, in the Bekaa Valley, in
two late morning runs.
   The spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said the planes also
dropped about six time bombs that exploded in a 10-minute period
after the air attack.
   The delayed blasts caused no other casualties, he said.
   Israeli authorities refused comment on the reported use of time
bombs. ``The Israeli Defense Forces do not give information about
weapons or ammunition that it uses,'' said the army spokesman, who
is not identified according to military regulations.
   Israel has reportedly used such explosives in the past in
Lebanon. Their use was reported in the initial days of Israel's
June 1982 invasion of Lebanon.
   Syrian soldiers manning surface-to-air missile batteries in the
Bekaa Valley did not fire on the Israeli jets, police said.
   The guerrillas opened up with twin-barreled anti-aircraft guns,
but witnesses said no hits were observed.
   On Thursday, four Israeli F-4 Phantom fighter-bombers struck
bases of the Popular Front in Sultan Yaaqoub and the adjacent Deir
Zanoun. One fighter was killed and four were wounded.
   The raid was the 16th Israeli air strike on guerrilla bases in
Lebanon this year. By police count, 18 people were killed and 107
wounded in the earlier raids.
   The Popular Front, led by former Syrian army captain Ahmed
Jibril, is opposed to peace overtures by Palestine Liberation
Organization chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Jibril's faction has been blamed for numerous terrorist attacks
and named in news reports as a suspect in the December 1988 bombing
of a Pan Am jetliner over Scotland. The explosion killed 270
people. Jibril denied his group was involved.
</TEXT>
