<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-American     11-25 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-American,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candidate's American Wife Becomes Asset</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Honduras, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting a0528 to remove extraneous material at end.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NACAOME, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Mary de Flores steps to the front
of the podium, a thrill runs through the small crowd at a Liberal
Party rally.
   ``It's Mary! It's Mary!'' squealed an 8-year-old girl,
stretching to see the woman in jeans and a red blouse accepting
presents from a group of small children.
   ``Her Spanish is really awful,'' remarked another resident of
this southern Honduran city. ``But she seems very nice.''
   Mary de Flores, born in New Orleans, has made another convert
for her husband Carlos Flores, who wants to be elected president of
Honduras on Sunday.
   ``I was always the shyest in the whole school,'' Mrs. Flores
said in an interview with The Associated Press. ``I could never get
up before a big group of people in English, and now I have to do it
in Spanish.''
   It's not the life she visualized when she met the energetic
young engineering student who became her husband at Louisiana State
University.
   ``My father was an engineer,'' she said. ``I kind of expected
that kind of life.''
   She did not expect the poverty that afflicts Honduras, a poverty
so deep that she reveals her age _ 37 _ but not her birthday.
   ``If they know my birthday, really poor people give me presents.
You feel ...,'' she trailed off. ``It's hard to take from people
who have nothing. Someone is making $40 a month and they spend $4
to buy you some flowers.''
   She has two children and works with poor children at a local
hospital.
   ``You see children with kwashiorkor, they've gone for so long
their bodies can't function. Dozens of kids die of measles. That
would never happen in the States. You see kids who drink turpentine
to get rid of worms, parents who sell eggs to buy cola.''
   She was attacked, especially in the Liberal Party primary, for
refusing to take Honduran citizenship.
   ``It's like trying to choose between two children,'' said Mrs.
Flores. ``I didn't come here to escape the United States. My
father, my brother, they fought for the United States.''
   Mrs. Flores would like to do what many Hondurans do and hold
dual citizenship, but she said U.S. officials told her she was too
prominent a personality to take Honduran citizenship without
renouncing U.S. citizenship.
   The issue faded when it became clear Mary de Flores could
connect with the voters.
   ``She's an asset. She is not faking it, and people know that,''
said Flores, who narrowly trails his chief opponent, Rafael
Leonardo Callejas of the National Party.
   ``Sometimes I feel uncomfortable with the upper classes. The
poor people, they remind me of my grandparents, they were cotton
farmers in Tennessee. When I smell a wood fire, it's nostalgic,''
said Mrs. Flores.
   ``The poor have so much faith in what Carlos is saying. When
those people are so poor and so concentrated, you feel an enormous
responsibility,'' she said.
   ``Carlos is optimistic about the future, though. I'm optimistic
because he's optimistic,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
