<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-WarGames     11-25 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-War Games,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Navy, Revolutionary Guards to Hold Joint Naval Maneuvers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Iranian navy said
Saturday his naval forces and the Islamic Revolutionary Guards
Corps will conduct joint maneuvers in the Persian Gulf and the Sea
of Oman next month, Tehran television reported.
   The broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Rear Adm. Ali
Shamkhani as saying the week of war games will concentrate on
training and coordinating the activities of the navy and the
Revolutionary Guards Corps.
   The joint maneuvers follow the merger of the Revolutionary
Guards Ministry and the Defense Ministry, which oversees Iran's
regular forces, earlier this year. The two ministries were merged
to streamline the military chain of command.
   Lack of coordination between the Revolutionary Guards and the
armed forces led to a string of battlefield defeats for Iran in the
eight-year Iran-Iraq war.
   The maneuvers, which begin sometime in mid-December, will be the
first since Shamkhani was appointed head of the navy by the
country's spiritual leader, Ali Khamenei, last month.
   The former head, Rear Adm. Mohammad Hussein-Malekzadegan, was
abruptly replaced as the head of the 14,500-man navy.
   The Iranians held their last naval maneuvers in the Persian Gulf
in mid-October.
   During those war games, Iraq accused two Iranian gunboats of
attacking an Iraqi tugboat and of killing one crewman.
   Iran's U.N. Ambassador, Kamal Kharrazi, denied that accusation.
He said two Iranian boats had been attacked by an Iraqi vessel in
late October and a crewman taken prisoner.
   There has been some disagreement among top Iranian leaders on
what to do about having two separate fighting forces within the
country.
   After his election in July, President Hashemi Rafsanjani said
the Revolutionary Guards would be merged with the regular armed
forces.
   But earlier this month Khamenei said such a merger would not
take place.
   The merger seems to be limited to the level of administration.
</TEXT>
