<FIRST>r a AM-Massacre-Witness     11-25 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Massacre-Witness,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness to Priest Killings Flies to Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cleaning woman who is the only known witness to
the massacre of six Jesuit priests in El Salvador slipped into
Miami with help from diplomats of four nations, officials said.
   The woman took shelter at the Spanish Embassy in San Salvador
after the Nov. 16 attack during renewed violence in the nation's
decade-long civil war. Late Thursday, she flew with her husband and
daughter to Miami aboard a French military plane, officials said.
   Lucia Barrera Cerna, 40, was turned over to the State Department
and remained in Miami on Friday, said Bernard Kouchner, the French
assistant secretary for humanitarian action who accompanied the
family.
   ``This lady is risking her life,'' Kouchner said. ``You know
Salvador. Who is able to guarantee any life in Salvador? You know
the history of violence and assassination.''
   The woman was brought to the United States ``in the interests of
cooperating fully with President (Alfredo) Cristiani's efforts to
bring the murderers to justice,'' State Department press officer
Dave Denny said Saturday. ``A Salvadoran investigator from the
Special Investigative Unit will be traveling to the United States
to take her deposition.''
   The Miami Herald, quoting unidentified sources, said the FBI was
guarding the family.
   But FBI spokesman Charles Steinmetz, contacted Saturday in
Washington, would say only that the FBI was helping investigate the
slayings. ``Our standard policy is not to comment about ongoing
investigations, so we have no comment about the details of that
investigation,'' he said.
   Barrera was likely to be moved at irregular intervals for her
own protection, Kouchner said.
   Salvadoran Attorney General Mauricio Colorado has quoted the
woman, who worked as a housekeeper at Central American University,
as saying she saw men ``dressed in military uniforms'' killing the
Jesuits, their housekeeper and her daughter.
   Jose Maria Tojeira, the highest-ranking Jesuit in Central
America, has said that Barrera, a university employee for 10 years,
reported 30 military men rounded up the priests and shot them
point-blank in a campus garden.
   ``Inside Salvador, it was impossible to protect'' the family,
Kouchner said. ``There were death squadrons all around.''
   The family's flight received multinational support.
   ``A departure was worked out in conjunction with the Salvadoran
government and French, Spanish, U.S. and British officials,'' said
American Embassy spokesman Jeff Brown.
   Even with approval to leave from the Salvadoran government,
Kouchner said, the family required extensive protection as they
left their homeland.
   ``We transferred the lady under the protection of our bodyguards
and security people from the French and Spanish embassies,'' he
said. ``The American ambassador was there. We all protected the
lady, and I delivered the lady here in Miami.''
   U.S. Ambassador William Walker had said the United States would
do everything possible to obtain the testimony of witnesses and
would offer them protection if necessary.
</TEXT>
