<FIRST>r i AM-EastGermany     11-25 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany,0613</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Say Prosecutions Possible for Ousted Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt ^By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Egon Krenz made a
campaign-style visit Saturday to the opposition stronghold of
Leipzig in his latest effort to portray himself as a popular
reformer and survive a crucial party congress.
   A Communist Party newspaper said some of the leadership under
Erich Honecker, who was ousted Oct. 18, may be prosecuted for
corruption.
   Hundreds of thousands of East Germans headed to West Berlin and
West Germany for more shopping, the third weekend of their new
freedom to travel, one of several reforms since Krenz took over.
   Parliament Speaker Guenther Maleuda said in an interview
published by the youth newspaper Junge Welt that parliamentary
elections could come as early as autumn 1990 if a new election law
is passed.
   Krenz's Leipzig visit, broadcast on state TV, was another
attempt to disassociate himself from his mentor's hard-line
policies and present himself as a populist. TV footage showed him
surrounded by workers and shoppers in what seemed like a campaign
stop.
   ``I don't think socialism is kaput,'' Krenz said. ``I think the
disfigurements of socialism are kaput.''
   Citizens grilled him about the country's moribund economy and
the government's sincerity in dealing with corruption.
   ``Come down on Mondays and talk to us,'' said one young man in
the city, where hundreds of thousands have taken to the streets
each Monday. ``Then things will get better in Leipzig.''
   Krenz praised Leipzig for giving ``many impulses'' to the
current promises of reforms.
   Opposition leaders say Krenz's past in Honecker's inner circle
will continue to block his efforts to gain popular support. The TV
report on Krenz's tour appeared aimed at boosting the leader's
image at a time of little trust or sympathy with Communist Party
stalwarts.
   Krenz reportedly faces strong opposition to his continued
leadership within the party now split on how to proceed with
reforms. He has admitted that he could be replaced at next month's
party congress.
   On Saturday, the Communists' daily newspaper, Neues Deutschland,
said members of Honecker's government could be prosecuted for cases
of ``misuse of power, corruption and personal enrichment.''
   Honecker himself is the target of a party disciplinary
proceeding and one of his top lieutenants was stripped of his
membership.
   The newspaper said party disciplinary proceedings were under way
or planned against other former officials. It did not mention names.
   ``Those who have made themselves guilty will be brought to
accountability by the party and, where necessary by judicial
officials and other agencies, both in criminal and disciplinary
proceedings,'' the newspaper quoted chief party investigator Werner
Eberlein as saying.
   In Hamburg, the Bild am Sonntag quoted opposition leader
Wolfgang Schnur as proposing West German President Richard von
Weizsaecker as the head of state for both German nations, in a step
toward possible reunification.
   Schnur is a member of the Democratic Awakening, which is smaller
and generally considered more conservative than the better known
New Forum opposition group.
   The official ADN news agency said an East Berlin policeman
sentenced to jail on charges of injuring a pro-democracy protester
was placed back on the force on suspended duty.
   The move by Police Chief Friedhelm Rausch followed a court
ruling Friday that found the policeman guilty of pushing a
demonstrator down stairs after an Oct. 7 rally. The court sentenced
him to 14 months in prison but an appeal is expected.
   Rausch was quoted as saying the policeman was reinstated because
the court used his dismissal after the incident as proof of guilt.
</TEXT>
