<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonRiot-Charges     11-25 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Riot-Charges,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Police Make Arrest In Camp Hill Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An state prison inmate whose sentence was
to have expired Saturday was the first to be charged because of two
nights of riots last month in which 123 guards and inmates were
injured, police said.
   State police at Harrisburg said more arrests were pending in
connection with the violence at Camp Hill State Prison, but they
would not give specifics on when or how many.
   William Diggs, 25, was arraigned Friday at the prison on charges
of riot, kidnapping, assault by prisoner, criminal attempt to arson
and making terroristic threats. Bond was set at $500,000.
   Inmates seized control of the medium-security prison Oct. 25 and
26, terrorizing guards, taking several hostages and setting fire to
many of the buildings in the 52-acre compound.
   The riots caused $15 million in damages. Gov. Robert P. Casey
suspended one prison official and has ordered a complete
investigation into claims that locks broken on the first night were
not fixed, allowing inmates to pop cell doors open for the second
night of rioting.
   No details of the charges against Diggs were released, and
authorities stopped short of calling him a ringleader in the
rioting.
   Cumberland County District Attorney J. Michael Eakin issued a
statement saying Diggs' sentence on a previous offense was to
expire Saturday and police wanted to file the charges before he was
released from prison.
   ``The timing of these charges relates to the defendant's
impending release from custody and should not be construed as
indicative of greater complicity than that alleged in the
charges,'' the statement said.
   Diggs was serving 3 to 6 years on a conviction for robbery and
conspiracy in Philadelphia.
   Eakin said the criminal investigation is continuing. ``We will
begin filing charges for the majority of incidents in several
weeks,'' he said.
   Kenneth Robinson, press secretary for the Department of
Corrections, was out of town and could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
