<FIRST>r a AM-Czechs-US 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 11-25 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechs-US, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Czechs React to Political Changes Sweeping Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th and 9th graf to CORRECT spelling to `Herrmann,' sted
`Hermann.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans of Czechoslovakian heritage were mostly cheered by the
political changes taking place in the eastern European nation, but
many of them tempered their feelings with skepticism.
   ``Boy, this is great _ if it's for real,'' said Glenn W.
Zajicek, former mayor of Wilber, the self-professed Czech capital
of Nebraska.
   ``I have to see it to believe it,'' said Dolores Pavlik, who
lives at the Notre Dame Convent in Omaha, Neb.
   The hard-line Communist Party leadership in Czechoslovakia
resigned Friday, forced from power by a week of huge pro-democracy
protests. But the new government is dominated by officials who also
served the previous regime.
   ``We have to watch the members of that (new) Politburo to see
what direction they will take,'' said Jan Vaculik, editor of a
Czech-language newspaper in the small central Texas town of West.
   Vaculik, who left Czechoslovakia a month after the Soviet
invasion in 1968, said the change isn't yet as sweeping as what has
happened in East Germany. But he said: ``I'm excited at least that
these guys are gone. I always feared that they may turn violent
against the people.''
   One of the speakers at rallies in Czechoslovakia was Alexander
Dubcek, the reformist former party leader ousted in 1968 when
Soviet troops invaded. In the teens, Dubcek's father had immigrated
to the United States, but he returned home after spending 14 months
in an internment camp in Texas for refusing to serve in the
military. Dubcek was born in 1921, after his father returned home.
   In Chicago, Dagmar Herrmann, a Czechoslovakian-born translator
who left her homeland in 1965, said Saturday she visited there
several times this year on business and felt this month's upheaval
``truly was unexpected.''
   ``They must have been as astonished as we were here,'' Herrmann
said. ``Nothing was truly planned, the same way it had been in
Poland. Czechoslovakia doesn't have anything like Solidarity. It
doesn't have opposition parties the same as Hungary had.''
   ``The Czechs are not truly people with their blood boiling. They
are quite stoic,'' she said.
   A woman who fled Czechoslovakia with her husband in 1949 and
settled in Nebraska told the Omaha World-Herald on Friday that she
didn't believe reformers in the Czechoslovak Communist Party can be
trusted.
   ``I don't trust communists,'' she said. ``They lie like it's
nothing.''
   The woman said she didn't want to be identified for fear of
retaliation against her mother and two sisters who still live in
Czechoslovakia. She hasn't seen them in 40 years.
   ``We're scared. We're scared for our people over there,'' she
said.
   Irma Ourecky, director of the Czech Musuem in Wilber, Neb., was
more optimistic. ``No one really knows,'' she said. ``But it seems
like, with the (Berlin) Wall down now, things will be different.''
   In Granger, Texas, a town about 80 miles south of West that is
also predominantly Czech, residents also are watching events
overseas.
   ``It looks like they might finally get some freedom, but it's
hard to judge,'' said Jannine Lalla, who visited Czechoslovakia 11
years ago. ``They're a complicated outfit over there. The people
are so nice, but they are afraid.''
   Joe Vrabel of Granger publishes ``Nasinec,'' a 75-year old
Czech-language weekly newspaper, but has never sold the paper to
residents in Czechslovakia. He hopes the changes pro-democracy
demonstrators seek will make it easier for him to do so.
   ``I never thought it would be free there again,'' he said
Friday. ``I've been thinking, just today, about selling the paper
in Czechoslovakia.''
</TEXT>
