<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSHome     11-25 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Home,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Home Closes; Former Member Cites Mismanagement, Conflict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A home for AIDS victims that was allowed
to open only after a federal court battle with the city has closed
after less than 2{ months because of financial problems and public
ill will, its chairman says.
   Keith Thomas, chairman of the Our Place board of directors and a
volunteer at the house, said the board voted unanimously Nov. 18 to
close the home.
   Our Place was intended to house up to seven men. At least two
AIDS victims lived there until their deaths.
   ``The house was shut down officially last weekend,'' Thomas
said. ``We voted to shut it down because of the ill feelings from
the public toward the home, the missappropriation of funds and
in-house fighting between Anna Berry and Charles Baxter.''
   But Ms. Berry, former administrator of the home, said Friday
that Our Place was closed because of a lack of funds, adding that
she got along well with Baxter, who founded Our Place.
   ``The reason the board decided to dissolve (Our Place) was there
was not enough money to keep it going,'' she said. ``Charles and I
were not fighting.''
   Thomas said he began working as a volunteer when the home opened
to balance the books and help residents.
   ``The money was not spent the way it was intended to be spent
when it was donated,'' Thomas said. ``I was a volunteer trying to
set up the books. I know there was mismanagement.''
   Baxter, a nurse's aide with no previous experience running a
boarding house, battled with city officials for several months for
permission to open the house. He filed suit and U.S. District Judge
William Stiehl ordered the city to grant him a permit, ruling that
the denial of a permit violated the Fair Housing Act.
   ``Irrational hysteria and public panic cannot support activity
that ... is clearly discriminatory,'' the judge wrote.
   Baxter got the permit Sept. 5 and the home opened Sept. 10.
   Baxter said the downtown building that he chose for Our Place
was ideal because it had a hospice next door, a hospital down the
street and a doctor's office in the back.
   City officials had argued that the home was too close to a
junior high school and was in a too-heavily traveled part of town.
Other concerns included that it would cause property values to
decline and people to avoid the area.
   Thomas said the board, made up of professionals including a
psychologist, hopes to open another home for people with AIDS.
   There was no comment from Baxter; there was no reply Saturday to
a message left on an answering machine at a listing for him in
Belleville. Someone who answered the phone at Ms. Berry's home said
she was not there.
</TEXT>
