<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonist     11-25 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Briton Cancels Plans for Balloon Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIYAKONOJO, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British businessman who hoped to set
a new distance record in a hot-air balloon canceled the trip early
Sunday because of weather-related damage to the craft that will
take months to repair.
   ``I'm terribly sorry, but we're not going to be able to take
off,'' a dejected Richard Branson said as the balloon was being
deflated behind him, changing from a towering, shimmering mass into
a limp rag the size of a baseball field.
   Branson and his co-pilot, Per Lindstrand, said frost had stuck
parts of the balloon to the ground when it was laid out Friday
night, and when it was inflated Saturday night the fabric ripped.
   The two planned to make a 6,200-mile flight across the Pacific
and land on the West Coast of the United States early this week.
   They had hoped to take off early Sunday after winds forced them
to call off a launch Friday night.
   Local officials in this town on the southern Japanese island of
Kyushu had to scrap a special fireworks show they had planned for
Friday's launch, and the cancellation sent hundreds of disappointed
townspeople walking back down a 1.5-mile-long hill they had climbed
to the launchpad.
   Branson, founder of Virgin Atlantic Airways and the Virgin Music
Group, already holds the distance record for hot-air ballooning for
a trip he and Lindstrand made across the Atlantic Ocean in 1987.
That trip almost ended in disaster when the huge craft flew out of
control and crashed into the sea off Scotland.
   Branson said the repair work on the new balloon will take
months. ``But we will be back in January or February, and I hope
that time we have better luck,'' he said.
</TEXT>
