<SECOND>AM-Germany-Protest,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militants Clash With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOETTINGEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bottle-hurling masked militants
clashed with hundreds of police Saturday after a protest march by
about 15,000 leftists turned violent.
   Ten police officers and at least one militant were injured in
the melee. Fifteen people were arrested, including eight in the
violence, police said.
   People from across West Germany took part in the march
protesting the Nov. 18 death of a 24-year-old woman hit by a car
while police chased her during a demonstration.
   Violence erupted Saturday when scores of militants turned over a
police car in the middle of the city after the protest, witnesses
said.
   Hundreds of riot police converged on the area, and were
bombarded with bottles, stones and metal objects hurled by the
militants, according to witnesses.
   Masked militants among the protesters broke windows at 14
businesses and a police station along the way, said police, who
confiscated air pistols, clubs and spray-paint cans.
   Thousands of police officers sealed off the streets of this city
in Lower Saxony before the protest, which drew members of West
Germany's opposition Social Democratic Party, the leftist Greens,
trade unions and church groups.
   The Nov. 18 death occurred after neo-Nazi ``skinheads'' and
masked leftist protesters battled in Goettingen and police moved in
to make arrests. The woman protester was hit by a car while fleeing
from police.
   Activists say she was not involved in the fighting and that
police had no right to pursue her.
