<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria     11-25 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists Dismantle Police Ideology Squad</HEAD>
<UNK>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist leadership on Saturday
dismantled a police squad that cracked down on human rights
activists and political opponents, the state BTA news agency
reported.
   It was the latest in a series of reforms since the Communists
replaced hard-line chief Todor Zhivkov on Nov. 10 and joined the
change that has washed over every Warsaw Pact nation except Romania.
   The decision came one week after 50,000 Bulgarians _ in the
largest protest since Bulgaria became a Communist nation _ rallied
for more democracy, free elections, respect of human rights and an
end to 45 years of police repression.
   Interior Minister Georgi Tanev, after a meeting with new party
leader Petar Mladenov, took away ``a number of functions'' from the
police ideological department and made assignments ``to other state
and public institutions in the spirit of the deep democratic
changes in Bulgaria,'' BTA said.
   The activity of the ideological department will be ``transformed
toward protection of the constitutional order (and) the rights and
freedoms of the citizens,'' BTA quoted Tanev as saying.
   While Tanev did not elaborate, he said the structure of the
ministry would be simplified and its staff reduced.
   ``In the past ... mistakes have been made, there has been an
inclination toward actions based on force at the expense of ...
dialogue,'' BTA said.
   BTA described the police unit as responsible for cracking down
on ``ideological diversion'' and human rights activists. Until Nov.
17, when Parliament scrapped it, Bulgaria had a law forbidding
dissent.
   Last week, Bulgaria's new reform-minded leadership set up a
commission to investigate alleged corruption under Zhivkov.
   Zhivkov, who had been in power for 35 years, has been accused of
living in luxury at the expense of the people, and at recent
rallies protesters demanded he be prosecuted.
</TEXT>
