<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BabySwap     11-25 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby Swap,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Families Come to Grips With Realization That Babies Were Swapped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parents in one family are collecting
pictures to send to a daughter they have yet to meet. A father in
another home 65 miles away copes with the devastating news he had a
daughter he will never meet.
   The players in the drama that intertwined two families and one
little girl are Ernest and Regina Twigg of Sebring and Robert Mays
of Sarasota and the girl he raised, Kimberly.
   The Twiggs and Mays discovered last Sunday that they raised each
other's child. Kimberly and another girl, Arlena, were born in 1978
in a Florida hospital, swapped and each given to the wrong family.
   Arlena Twigg, Mays' biological daughter, died last year of heart
disease long before he learned of the swap. They never met.
   ``I feel a sense of loss,'' Mays said last week. ``Just what I
lost is hard to say. Obviously I've lost a daughter, but I didn't
know the little girl. I don't have a personality to remember or a
face to remember or anything like that.
   ``I really feel like I had two daughters; one lived and one
died.''
   Mays, a 44-year-old roofing contractor, raised Kimberly, who
will celebrate her 11th birthday Wednesday.
   Genetic testing showed that Kimberly was really born to the
Twiggs, parents of seven other children.
   The child the Twiggs named Arlena and reared as their own was
the daughter of Mays and his late wife, Barbara, who died of cancer
in 1981.
   Both families say a switch occurred at Hardee Memorial Hospital
in Wauchula but they have no idea how. The Mays baby was born on
Nov. 29 and the Twigg baby on Dec. 2, 1978.
   The Twiggs are suing the hospital, and Mays is considering it.
Officials at the hospital have refused to comment on the issue.
   Just before Arlena died in Pennsylvania in August 1988, the
Twiggs discovered through genetic testing she was not related to
either of them.
   After her death, they began a 14-month search for their missing
daughter.
   It brought them to Kimberly Michelle Mays, the only other white
girl in the nursery at the rural Florida hospital at the same time.
   The Twiggs waged a custody battle in court as Mays resisted
genetic testing. He sought the expertise of child pschologists who
advised against it.
   This fall the Twiggs moved their family back to central Florida
to be closer to Kimberly. Twigg, whose children range in age from 6
to 21, got back his old job as an Amtrak ticket agent in Sebring.
   Finally, in late October, they broke the impasse by signing an
agreement renouncing any claim on Kimberly no matter whose child
she was. But they wanted visitation privileges, and promised to let
psychologists for both sides interview the girl and suggest a
schedule.
   On Nov. 17, results of sophisticated series of blood-protein
tests were returned from Johns Hopkins Medical Center in Baltimore.
The tests, which analyze genes, determined with a 99.9 percent
certainty that Kimberly was a Twigg and with a 98.9 percent
certainty that Arlena was a Mays.
   Both families shared their feelings publicly last week through
tears: tears of joy for the Twiggs that they had found their lost
daughter and tears of pain for Mays, who had to explain to his only
child she wasn't his biological daughter.
   Mays spoke Wednesday about the trauma of telling Kimberly.
   ``She cried and cried and cried for a long time,'' he said. Then
she asked what it meant about their relationship.
   He said he assured her, ``Honey, you'll always be my daughter,''
and told her nothing would change.
   ``I hope desperately we can continue to have the relationship
and the happiness we've shared,'' he said in an interview later.
``I was perfectly happy with our life prior to this, and I think
she was, too. I told her that it had no significance in our life
whatsoever.''
   The Twiggs want their first meeting with Kimberly to be special.
They plan to send family pictures first, then perhaps meet with her
alone _ without their other children.
   ``We'll take it slow,'' Mrs. Twigg said.
   Mays won't talk about his own hurt. ``I'll have the rest of my
life to sort out my feelings as to what happened,'' said Mays.
   He wants to know where Arlena is buried. His attorney has asked
the Twiggs' lawyer for the location of the grave. He said he'll
visit the site as soon as he can.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891125-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WatsonvilleVoting     11-25 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Watsonville Voting,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake-Ravaged City Holds Delayed Court-Ordered Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WATSONVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the city is trying to rebuild
following the devastating October earthquake, a court-ordered
change in how the city council is elected will shake up municipal
leadership.
   The Dec. 5 election will mark a switch from at-large to district
elections, mandated by a federal court to give Hispanics fair
representation on the city council.
   ``When we look back 10 or 15 years from now and we see
significant Hispanic participation in voting, Watsonville will be
seen as a catalyst for that change,'' said Joaquin Avila, the
attorney who represented the Mexican-American Legal Defense and
Education Fund in the lawsuit.
   The lawsuit, filed by the fund in 1985 on behalf of three
plaintiffs, alleged the at-large system discriminated against
Hispanics. Although about half the city of 30,000 was Hispanic,
until then no Hispanic had ever been elected to the council. The
lawsuit was one of many filed by members of minority groups seeking
to overturn at-large voting in cities across the country.
   Earlier this year, the U.S. Supreme Court rejected the city's
attempt to overturn an appeals court's order to create district
voting.
   The election, originally scheduled for May 9, was postponed
until Nov. 7 to allow time to develop the district plan. After the
Oct. 17 earthquake, the election was postponed again; the disaster
destroyed more than 300 homes and damaged 1,900 and displaced
dozens of businesses in the town 95 miles south of San Francisco.
   Sixteen candidates, five of them Hispanic, are vying for seven
seats on the new council, which will choose a mayor from among the
council members and work with the more powerful city manager. Three
incumbents are seeking re-election.
   Housing and development, big issues last spring, have become
even bigger since the earthquake, with 135 families still living in
tents or shelters and many more staying with friends or relatives.
   Councilman Tony Campos, a wealthy real estate agent who
inspected many of the cracked buildings, last week estimated damage
at $179 million to businesses and $165 million to homeowners.
Earlier official estimates put the total damage in the city at $112
million.
   The most important business downtown, Ford's, built in 1852 and
the oldest department store in California, succumbed to a wrecking
ball last week.
   Ford's, a $40 million company that also lost two other stores in
the quake, hasn't decided yet whether to rebuild a big store in
Watsonville.
   That decision, and many others that businesses must make,
depends largely on the availability of financing and the speed with
which the city can put together a recovery plan and obtain federal
and state help.
   ``We're going to have to have people who can make decisions,''
said Campos, who became the first Hispanic council member in 1987.
``We're in trouble right now. The earthquake was bad enough. If we
lose these businesses the economic aftershocks will cripple
Watsonville completely.''
   Mayor Betty Murphy, who is running against Campos in District 6,
dismisses the notion that the city, which sits in the center of a
rich agricultural area, could be headed for oblivion.
   ``This is a very strong, personal and old community,'' she said.
``It won't be any ghost town, but it is going to be difficult.''
   Campos and Murphy are stressing the need for experience and
continuity on the new council, arguing that an inexperienced
council can slow recovery.
   Campos opposed the voting rights suit.
   ``If the elections would have been left the way they were, you
would probably have four or five Hispanics on the city council, if
not this year then within the next two-year term,'' he said. ``One
of the worst things they did was file this lawsuit. It's pitting
two incumbents (Campos and Murphy) against each other and causing
some friction in the community.''
   Cruz Gomez, a candidate in District 1, is among those calling
for change, especially in regard to the attention paid to poorer
Hispanic residents.
   Gomez opposes re-electing Campos and the candidacy of another
Hispanic, saying they don't represent poor Hispanics.
   ``We have to go by issues and action, and not by skin color or
origin,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
