<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-25 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winter-Like Storm Developing Along West Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wintry storm came ashore on the northern Pacific Coast on
Saturday, threatening up to 3 feet of snow in the mountains, and
storm watches were posted all the way to the Rockies.
   Rain fell at lower elevations. Snow began falling on the coastal
mountain ranges of Washington, Oregon and Northern California.
   Two to 3 feet of snow was possible in the northern Sierra Nevada
range in California, the National Weather Service said.
   ``Travel across the Sierra should be avoided if at all possible
during this storm,'' the weather service warned.
   The weather was welcomed by ski resort operators in the Sierra,
who have had a poor season so far.
   ``It couldn't be better,'' said Doug Garver, manager at Boreal
Ski Area. He said snow started falling there Thursday and ``hasn't
stopped since.''
   Four to 8 inches of snow was expected by Sunday morning in south
central Oregon, the weather service said.
   Farther inland, winter storm watches were posted through Sunday
for the mountains of Utah and Utah's northern valleys, the
mountains of southern Idaho and southern Montana, western Wyoming
and the Colorado Rockies.
   From Friday night into Saturday, snow fell across the Colorado
Rockies, with up to 12 inches at Gothic, 10 inches at Berthoud Pass
and 9 inches at Mary Jane and Steamboat, the weather service said.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms drenched the Florida Keys.
Key West was soaked with 2.30 inches of rain late Friday and got an
additional 3.25 inches during the six hours up to 1 p.m. EST.
   A few showers and thunderstorms spread along the central Gulf
Coast.
   A few light showers developed along a cold front over Iowa and
eastern Nebraska. In the Northeast, light snow showers extended
over northern New England and upstate New York.
   Temperatures remained in the 50s overnight in Southern
California and southern Arizona. The morning low of 55 degrees at
Riverside, Calif., was the city's warmest on record for the date.
   At the other extreme, lows were in the teens in northern
Minnesota and Upper Michigan, and across much of the Northeast,
with temperatures in single digits in northern Maine. Allentown,
Pa., tied its record low for the date of 16 degrees.
   The low for the Lower 48 states was 1 degree above zero at
Houlton, Maine.
</TEXT>
