<FIRST>r a AM-DefenseCuts     11-25 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Cuts,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Secretary Cheney Implies Army Facing Biggest Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said the United
States must maintain naval superiority and modernize strategic
nuclear weapons, implying budget cuts might hit the Army hardest,
the Los Angeles Times said Saturday.
   In an interview in Washington on Friday, Cheney suggested that
the job of maintaining ground forces in Europe could be left to
North Atlantic Treaty Organization allies, the Times said.
   Cheney, who emphasized that the NATO balance would not be
changed unilaterally by the United States, said one scenario would
have the allies take the main role of ground defense while the U.S.
upgrades naval and air forces in the alliance.
   ``Should the U.S., as some have suggested, take on a role that
emphasizes more heavily the U.S. obligation in the naval area and
in air supremacy and places a greater emphasis with our allies in
terms of the ground combat role in Europe?'' Cheney asked. ``All of
those issues it seems to me are up for grabs.''
   He also said: ``The U.S. is now and will want to continue to be
the pre-eminent naval power in the world,'' even as the nation's
overall defense budget is subjected to cuts.
   Cheney also said ``we're going to want to preserve our strategic
nuclear capability,'' adding that preservation of adequate
conventional forces would be another demand.
   The secretary said he remained skeptical about reforms in the
Soviet Union.
   ``I still think vigilance is the order of the day,'' he said.
``I still think we have to be very cautious about assuming that Mr.
(Mikhail) Gorbachev will be successful, or assuming that his
successors will be more like him than like conventional Soviet
leaders: Brezhnev, Khrushchev, Stalin, etc.''
</TEXT>
