<FIRST>r a AM-SeditionTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0575 11-25 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sedition Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0575,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates For 17th Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with jury recessing for day, no
verdict reached; picks up 5th graf, ``Haldiman said ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors deliberated for the 17th day
Saturday in the sedition trial of three people, reviewing testimony
by an FBI currency analyst and giving little hint of what was
happening in the jury room.
   The two men and a woman are accused of racketeering,
racketeering conspiracy and the arcane charge of seditious
conspiracy, which has been rarely used since it was invoked during
the Civil War to prosecute Confederate loyalists.
   Prosecutors allege that Raymond Levasseur, his wife, Patricia
Gros Levasseur, and Richard Williams were members of a terrorist
band that robbed banks and bombed buildings along the East Coast
from the mid-1970s to 1984.
   The jury recessed Saturday without reaching a verdict in the
trial, which has gone on for almost a year.
   The testimony requested was that of FBI Agent Donald Haldiman,
who testified about how money seized at the time of the defendants'
arrest was matched against Federal Reserve shipments.
   Haldiman said records showed the money had been sent to branches
of the Sovran Bank. The indictment alleges that Levasseur and
Williams were part of a group of four men who robbed the Norfolk,
Va., branch of the bank in June 1984.
   Earlier in the week, jurors asked to look at charts of
footprints taken at a bombing site.
   The prosecution based much of its case on notebooks allegedly
written by the defendants in an elaborate code that detailed
strategies and recorded minutes of meetings. Defense attorneys said
the books weren't a reliable record, terming them ``error-ridden
jottings.''
   Some legal observers have said the lengthy deliberations are to
be expected, considering that the trial has taken 11 months and
included testimony from about 200 witnesses. Evidence in the case
filled filing cabinets and boxes stacked in the courtroom.
   A trial in New York City involving some of the bombings
prosecutors allege the group took part in resulted in 19 days of
deliberations.
   The Springfield jury has diligently worked through weekends,
taking only one day off for Thanksgiving and one Saturday off while
a juror renewed her wedding vows. Jurors planned a half-day session
Sunday.
</TEXT>
