<FIRST>r a AM-Cuba 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0577,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>3 Activists Sentenced For Talking to Foreign Reporters About Drug
Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix garble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Havana court sentenced three Cuban human rights
activists to prison after convicting them of giving false
information to foreign journalists during a drug trial last summer,
the Cuban government news service reported.
   Elizardo Sanchez, Cuba's most outspoken internal critic, was
convicted and given a two-year sentence Friday, Prensa Latina
reported. Hiram Abi Cobas and Hubert Jerez were sentenced to 18
months each.
   The prosecution had asked for prison terms of three or four
years for the three activists.
   The three were arrested Aug. 6 on charges of ``spreading false
information against international peace'' in an attempt to
discredit Cuban courts when they spoke with U.S. television
networks and Radio Marti, a U.S. government station beamed to Cuba.
   The defendants were accused of telling U.S. media that Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa Sanchez had been psychologically tortured and had
confessed to drug trafficking while under the influence of drugs
administered by his interrogators.
   Granma, the official Cuban newspaper, said the three carried out
a ``campaign of slander'' aimed at ``discrediting the action of
Cuban courts'' during Ochoa's trial.
   Ochoa, a Cuban war hero, and three other men were executed in
July following trials that revealed a criminal ring in the Cuban
defense and interior departments that helped smuggle drugs from
Colombia to the United States.
   The trial and the corruption it revealed were extremely
embarrassing to Cuba's communist leader, Fidel Castro, who had
insisted for years that accusations of drug trafficking were part
of a U.S. plot to discredit his government.
   Sanchez, imprisoned for more than six years since 1972,
co-founded the Cuban Human Rights Committee in 1976 and the
Commission for Human Rights and National Conciliation in 1987. He
served eight months for a similar offense in 1986.
   Cobas is acting head of the Human Rights Party of Cuba, and
Jerez is president of the Jose Marti Commission on Human Rights.
</TEXT>
