<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovak-Reax     11-25 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovak-Reax,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Bloc Reaction to Czechoslovak Upheavals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czecholsovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News media in the East bloc on Saturday generally
lauded the political upheavals in Czechoslovakia that removed
hard-line Communist Party leaders but the dramatic events were
virtually unreported in Romania.
   Romanian party chief Nicolae Ceausescu has firmly opposed the
democratic reforms sweeping Eastern Europe and on Friday the
71-year-old Ceausescu was re-elected to another five-year term as
party leader.
   Soviet television's nightly news program Vremya said that as
changes transformed Poland, Hungary and East Germany the
Czechoslovak ``leaders _ now the country's former leaders _
repeated like prayers the words `order' and `quiet.' ''
   Vremya commentator Sergei Andreyev said in the broadcast from
Prague, ``Quiet, if you mean the synonym of stagnation, such quiet
is not needed by a country which has embarked on the road to
democratization.''
   Vremya praised the Czechoslovak protesters for maintaining order
during their massive protests.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass reported the Czechoslovak
Communist Party is willing to form a coalition government with
other parties.
   Although Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms are
credited with providing much of the impetus for the changes in
Eastern Europe, the Soviet Communist Party has given no indication
of accepting such a coalition arrangement.
   Tass quoted former Czechoslovak Communist Party leader Alexander
Dubcek as blaming his country's crisis on ``military interference
in the affairs and life of the Czechoslovak people.''
   Dubcek obviously referred to the Soviet-led Warsaw Pack invasion
of Czechoslovakia in August 1968, which crushed Dubcek's reform
administration that had introduced what became known as the
``Prague Spring.'' Dubcek was ousted and a hard-line party
leadership installed.
   The Soviet government has not renounced the invasion, but some
other East bloc countries have.
   Tass also said the Czechoslovak opposition did not seem to have
``a harmonious and clear-cut action program,'' and many people were
looking to the Communist Party ``to take the country out of the
crisis.''
   In Hungary, which is moving toward a full multi-party system,
the newspaper Magyar Nemzet said, ``The Prague Domino Has Fallen:
the Czechoslovak Party Leadership Resigned.''
   Polish party leader Mieczyslaw Rakowski congratulated Karel
Urbanek on his election as new general secretary of the
Czechoslovak Communist Party, sending wishes for the ``successful
development of social-political reforms in Czechoslovakia.'' Poland
has a coalition government and its premier, a former Solidarity
activist, is the first non-communist government leader in the
Eastern bloc.
   In non-aligned Yugoslavia, newspapers headlined the resignation
of Czechoslovakia's hard-line party leader Milos Jakes.
   ``People are embracing, champagne bottles are being opened,
columns of cars are rhythmically sounding their horns,'' said the
Belgrade daily Politika.
   A Belgrade Ekspres headline said: ``No one (stood) by Jakes.''
   In Jerusalem, former Soviet prisoner Natan Sharansky told Israel
Television that the changes in Eastern Europe made him feel
``exactly as I did when I was released.
   ``On the one hand you're afraid to believe it,'' he said.
``Maybe it's just another dream you're having while in solitary
confinement.''
   He spent nine years in Soviet prisons and labor camps before
being freed in an East-West exchange Feb. 11, 1986. He had been
sentenced to 13 years in 1978 on charges of anti-Soviet espionage
for his contacts with Western media and criticism of the Kremlin.
   Sharansky, 41, is the chairman of a Soviet Jewry Zionist Forum
group he founded two years ago to help Soviet Jewish immigrants
adjust to Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
