<DOCNO> AP891125-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 1917EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LeagueofCities     11-25 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-League of Cities,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Municipal Officials Cite Concerns, Press for Federal Funding, Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA WALSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National League of Cities' annual convention
opened Saturday with drug trafficking and getting federal help to
fight it key topics of discussion for America's mayors.
   Also on the agenda for discussion during the five-day meeting
are ways of dealing with such issues as pollution, ethics in
government and getting more money out of the federal government.
   About 4,500 municipal leaders are expected to attend the
convention.
   The league's president, Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard, said
convention discussions would center on the need for federal and
local action in the fight against drugs.
   ``Mayors are going to ... share experiences about what does work
and what doesn't,'' Goddard said in an interview. ``We need to make
a case to the federal government about the extent of what is going
on, because statements issued in Washington, D.C., show that they
don't really know.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle and Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Jack Kemp are scheduled to address the mayors on Monday.
   The mayors are hoping for more visible federal support for local
law enforcement agencies, New Orleans Mayor Sidney J. Barthelemy
said Saturday.
   ``I think all of us hope that the federal government will fund
cities directly; we are the front lines in the war against drugs,''
Barthelemy said. ``We feel the government should give less to the
generals, the state leaders, and more to us, the infantry doing the
fighting.''
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young planned to meet Sunday with other
mayors who are due to leave office this year for a panel discussion
about trends and changes in their cities.
   Young, an unannounced candidate for governor of Georgia, is
slated to receive the League's outstanding leadership award for his
contributions to the organization.
   On Tuesday, Children's Defense Fund President Marion Wright
Edelman is scheduled to speak. Environmental Protection Agency
administrator William Reilly is expected to address the mayors
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
