<FIRST>r i AM-OPEC     11-25 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Ministers Open Meeting, Try to End Production Cheating</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC oil ministers formally opened a
strategy meeting Saturday and then turned to private bargaining to
try to end production cheating by some of the 13 member nations.
   Several ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries said they wanted crude prices to go higher.
   ``I would like to see them rise,'' Saudi Arabian Minister Hisham
Nazer said at the start of the group's winter conference.
   Iran's Gholamreza Aqazadeh said the cartel ``must get'' to its
target price of $18 a barrel. A basket price of crudes monitored by
OPEC recently hit $17.76 a barrel.
   West Texas Intermediate, the American benchmark crude, has been
trading around $20 per barrel. Middle Eastern crudes run several
dollars less.
   The petroleum ministers, who arrived in Vienna several days ago
for informal talks, have as their goal a new production and pricing
agreement for the first half of 1990.
   OPEC's output ceiling now is 20.5 million barrels a day, but
actual production is estimated at more than 23 million barrels.
   OPEC President Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria told his colleagues the
market ``can easily absorb'' an average of at least 21 million
barrels a day next year.
   A stumbling block in arranging a production deal is demands by
Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates for bigger shares of the
cartel's output.
   Both have ignored the current accord and pump well over their
quotas. Their actions have angered other members who believe prices
would be higher with more restraint.
   During private discussions Saudi Arabia has proposed that some
countries, like Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates, be allowed to
produce more.
   ``I think it is a positive concept,'' said Kuwait's Ali Khalifa
al-Sabah. Kuwait, according to analysts, is pumping close to 2
million barrels a day, nearly double its quota.
   The United Arab Emirates' Mana Saeed Otaiba declined to say what
quota he wanted. He said his country is producing ``more than 2''
million barrels a day, or double its quota.
</TEXT>
