<FIRST>r a AM-Reporter'sFuneral     11-25 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reporter's Funeral,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral for Tampa Reporter Killed In Peru</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First name Ruel in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300 mourners packed a church
Saturday to remember a newspaper reporter slain in Peru while
investigating narcotics and terrorism there.
   The FBI has joined the probe into the slaying of Todd C. Smith,
28, of The Tampa Tribune, the newspaper reported.
   ``He went for the story,'' Ruel W. Tyson Jr., a friend of
Smith's family, told mourners at the funeral at St. John's
Episcopal Church. ``You see, it was part of his calling, his
assignment. Risk is a part of reporting.''
   Smith had been on vacation. His body was found Tuesday in the
remote town of Uchiza, with a placard nearby denouncing ``North
American spies.'' An autopsy revealed his neck had been broken and
found evidence he had been beaten.
   Authorities suspect the Shining Path, a Maoist guerrilla group,
in Smith's death.
   Smith was in the Upper Huallaga region of central Peru, which is
considered the world's largest source of the coca leaf used to make
cocaine. The area has been in turmoil since Shining Path guerrillas
recently started extorting payments from peasants and Colombian
traffickers to finance their effort.
   Smith, an expert on Latin America, had covered jungle warfare in
Central America. Although on vacation, he apparently was gathering
material for stories.
   Tyson told mourners that Smith's courage stemmed from his
devotion to his work. ``Todd's works, the practices of his calling
as reporter, are the most telling comments on his life,'' the
Chapel Hill, N.C., man told mourners.
   When Smith died, his focus was on his story, Tyson said.
   ``Todd did not live a life that calls for flamboyant terms,''
Tyson said. ``He was no hero. He was a reporter doing his job _
prudently, quietly and with spare prose.''
   Smith reportedly was last seen on Nov. 17, when he was to have
flown home. There were reports that he was overpowered at gunpoint
at the airport on the outskirts of Uchiza or kidnapped from a car
on the way to the airport.
   The FBI is working with the U.S. State Department and the
Peruvian government in the investigation into Smith's slaying, FBI
spokesman Mike Kortan in Washington told the Tribune.
   A memorial service for Smith is to be held Monday in Tampa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
