<DOCNO> AP891125-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Eastern-BombThreat     11-25 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Bomb Threat,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Blames Machinists For Bomb Threats on Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines blamed striking machinists for
bomb threats against a flight Saturday, claiming their union was
trying to frighten travelers away from the airline during the
holiday season.
   A spokesman for the Machinists union denied that union members
had anything to do with the threats.
   The Associated Press received a call warning that Eastern Flight
90 from Portland, Ore., to Atlanta, due in at 4:38 p.m. Saturday,
was the target of a bomb threat. The anonymous caller said he had
heard about the threat while monitoring air traffic.
   Other news media also received tips on alleged bomb threats,
according to the airline and the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak in Miami said the carrier
received several bomb threats involving Flight 90, including one
from a caller who identified himself as a striking Eastern mechanic.
   After the information was evaluated, the carrier determined the
threats were a hoax, she said. The flight was not disrupted.
   ``Whoever the caller or callers were, they spent more time
calling the media ... I think this is indicative of their (the
Machinists') shift in tactic to try and frighten travelers over the
holiday period,'' she said.
   Charles Bryan, president of Machinists District 100 in Miami,
denied strikers were involved.
   ``I can assure you we are not inolved with any illegal activity
or bomb threats ... that kind of activity can be traced, and we
encourage them (Eastern) to do so and stop the rhetoric,'' Bryan
said. ``We have rigorously and constantly told our membership not
to do anything illegal.''
   The Machinists vowed Friday to continue and intensify their
8{-month strike despite announcements Wednesday and Thursday that
the pilots and flight attendants were ending their walkouts, which
began in March in solidarity with the Machinists' 8,500 members.
   Another Eastern spokesman, Jim Ashlock, said strikers were
``trying to create a big stir, and this is a peak travel weekend. I
believe there's a direct relation between the (bomb threat) tips
and the union workers' announcement about changing tactics.''
   The FBI and the FAA were told about the threats, Ashlock said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
