<FIRST>u i AM-AirplaneBomb 1stLd-Writethru   11-25 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airplane Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0550,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>10 Passengers Questioned in Airplane Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to ADD background. Pickup 6th graf `Police
gave...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Flight 103, Bjt ^By IQBAL JAFFERY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said they were questioning 10
people Saturday who were among the 339 passengers aboard a Saudi
jumbo jet on which a bomb was found.
   Saudi Arabian Airlines said it was ``with God's blessing'' that
the defective time bomb did not explode on board the Boeing 747,
which was rerouted to this southern port city while flying from
Islamabad, Pakistan, to Riyadh, Saudi Arabia.
   While the plane was flying over the Arabian Sea on Thursday
night, airport security in Islamabad received an anonymous letter
threatening to blow the plane up unless a demand for $15 million
was met, officials said. Flight 367 landed safely in Karachi.
   Moinuddin, head of Pakistan's bomb disposal squad in Karachi,
said eight ounces of dynamite were found in an untagged school bag.
It was surrounded by clothes, a cigarette lighter and a box of
matches, said the official, who uses only one name.
   The bomb was set to go off 35 minutes after the jumbo jet took
off from Islamabad, officials said, but a battery apparently jarred
loose, detaching a wire to the detonator.
   In its statement issued in Jiddah, Saudi Arabia, the airline
said 332 adults and seven children were aboard.
   Police gave few details about the 10 passengers held for
questioning. ``We haven't laid any charges; we are just questioning
them,'' said a Karachi police official on condition of anonymity.
   He said all 10 were from Pakistan's North West Frontier Province.
   Islamabad police said they also were questioning a taxi driver
who delivered the extortion letter to an Islamabad airport officer
shortly after Flight 367 left Islamabad.
   The note demanded $15 million in ransom to be deposited in three
bags at a location in Islamabad, said the Saudi airline. Pakistani
police earlier put the figure at $1.5 million.
   No one has claimed responsibility for placing the bomb on the
plane, and police have refused to discuss possible suspects.
   A terrorist bomb exploded aboard a New York-bound Pan Am jumbo
jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988, killing all 259
people aboard and 11 people on the ground. Investigators determined
the explosion was caused by a bomb hidden in a cassette-recorder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
