<FIRST>r a AM-People-Keillor     11-25 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Keillor,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Live From Brooklyn, It's Garrison Keillor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Garrison Keillor returned to the air
Saturday night, saying it's great to be back on radio but that
broadcasting from Brooklyn instead of St. Paul, Minn. feels just a
bit strange.
   At the start of the live, two-hour program broadcast nationally
on public radio stations, Keillor wondered aloud whether anyone in
New York was listening.
   He said it felt ``just a bit odd to do a show in New York City.
You walk around the streets here and you see all the cars on the
streets with signs in the windows that say `no radio in car.' Sort
of feel like you've lost half your audience right there.''
   Keillor said he has learned it's safer in New York ``if you talk
to yourself. So I do that. English mostly. Danish for variety.''
   Saturday's premiere of ``Garrison Keillor's American Radio
Company of the Air'' from the Brooklyn Academy of Music featured a
humorous skit about upper-crust volunteers doomed to fund raising
for public television, satirical slaps at authors and booksellers,
an appeal by a fictitious group that helps clothe featherless
turkeys and several musical interludes.
   The show marked Keillor's return to radio after a two-year
absence that began when he ended ``A Prairie Home Companion,''
which drew 4 million listeners each week on public radio stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
