<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Fodor'sReturn     11-25 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fodor's Return,0382</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violinist Gives Benefit Performance After Drug-Related Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violinist Eugene Fodor gave a benefit
performance Saturday across the street from the courthouse where he
was sentenced last month on a drug-related charge.
   Fodor began with the ``Sonata in G Minor'' by Johann Sebastian
Bach. He dedicated the concert before an appreciative audience of
about 75 people at a church to a co-founder of Alcoholics Anonymous.
   ``It's not easy coming back, but I'm here because I want to face
my demons,'' Fodor said in an interview before the concert. ``I'm
grateful for my new health and I'm happy to be here on different
terms.''
   Fodor, 39, was arrested July 27 and convicted of breaking into a
Martha's Vineyard motel room. A search of the room turned up a
bottle containing more than 20 grams of cocaine, a hypodermic
needle with a small amount of heroin and a dagger.
   Fodor pleaded innocent to charges of possession, but after
pleading guilty to the breaking and entering charges he was
sentenced to three years' probation under which he is subject to
random drug testing.
   The violinist had planned Saturday night's concert as a gesture
to the community that he feels started him back on the right track.
   ``I'm grateful for the way my case was handled and for my
recovery and the fellowship I have found. It was here that the
intervention took place. That started me on the program of
sobriety.''
   Proceeds from the concert were to be donated to a drug education
program at the public schools on Martha's Vineyard, a resort island
south of Cape Cod.
   Fodor, an acclaimed violin virtuoso, won a silver medal in the
1974 Tchaikovsky Competition at age 24. After a period of dazzling
success, critics began accusing him of playing only showy
crowd-pleasing selections that lacked maturity. His career began to
tumble, reaching its nadir in the motel room arrest.
   Fodor, who recently spent 28 days in drug rehabilitation in New
York state, said his trials have had a positive effect on his music.
   ``I've found a new spirituality to my music,'' he said. ``I feel
I have never played better. I'm finding depth to my music I didn't
think was possible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
