<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Newspaper     11-25 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Newspaper,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist-Controlled Daily Newspaper Goes Out Of Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last issue of the Rome-based daily newspaper
Paese Sera appeared Saturday, just about two weeks shy of its 40th
birthday.
   The failure of the Communist-controlled newspaper follows years
of disputes between the management, the staff and the ownership
consortium that included the printers and the Italian Communist
Party.
   Paese Sera did not say how many people would be put out of work
by the closure, but the Rome newspaper Il Tempo said it would leave
44 journalists and an unspecified number of other employees
unemployed.
   The newspaper's printing house has said since March 1983 that
the newspaper was facing closure because of financial problems.
   Giuliano Prasca, a member of the editorial committee, told the
news agency that the newspaper had run up a deficit of
approximately $2.1 million over the past six years.
   The government-owned television RAI television network reported
that the newspaper's daily circulation stood at 11,000. Another
Communist newspaper, Il Manifesto, reported that Paese Sera would
have needed an average daily circulation of about 16,000 in order
to survive.
</TEXT>
