<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2202EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LotsofLeftovers     11-25 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lots of Leftovers,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food For Thought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PITTSBURGH, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A caterer whose plan to feed the
hungry backfired on Thanksgiving hasn't lost his spirit of giving,
and said Saturday that he plans to make free meals at his banquet
hall a regular event.
   It looked like John Kostik, 40, was going to be stuck with
hundreds of pounds of leftovers from a party planned for 900 needy
people for which only 24 showed up.
   But a food bank came to his rescue, saying it would not let the
food go to waste.
   ``It was the strangest Thanksgiving I've ever had,'' Kostik
recalled on Saturday.
   More volunteers showed up to help serve the food than people to
eat it.
   Kostik and his wife, Jane, 40, found about 80 people to give
food to Friday, but still had about 200 pounds of turkey, 210
pounds of potatoes, 60 cases of bulk corn and more than 200 pumpkin
pies left.
   ``We gave them a couple of turkeys each and some pies. We loaded
them up,'' Kostik said. ``We found the food bank as a result of all
the media attention we got.''
   The Greater Pittsburgh Community Food Bank will distribute the
food to poor families, said Joyce Rothermel, the group's executive
director.
   Kostik said he mailed dozens of announcements about the feast,
which cost him $1,000, to Pittsburgh-area newspapers and television
and radio stations, but apparently none was used.
   Volunteers posted fliers throughout the neighborhood, but that
didn't help much either.
   The only people who showed up were reporters who found out about
the free party to which few came.
   ``I hung up on the first television station that called that
afternoon. I didn't want them to make me any more depressed than I
already was. I didn't want to watch my empty banquet hall on TV
that night or read about it in the paper the next day,'' Kostik
said. ``But the attention turned out to be a real good thing after
all.''
   Kostik thinks his use of the word ``needy'' on the fliers
discouraged many people in his neighborhood from coming.
   ``We have a lot of ex-steelworkers here who have been unemployed
a long time and a lot of senior citizens on fixed incomes. They're
the kind of people who are too proud to ask for a handout,'' he
said.
   Kostik wants to try again. He plans to begin serving free meals
at least once a month at the banquet hall.
   ``I'll probably do that starting in December _ maybe every other
Tuesday _ for about 400 or 500 needy people,'' he said.
   But he'll probably rely on word of mouth to attract guests.
   ``On Friday, a lot of people told me if I do this again, they'll
bring a couple of their neigbors who are in the same situation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
