<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2219EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DesertRace     11-25 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Desert Race,0418</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desert Race Leaves 11 Cyclists Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARSTOW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,100 cyclists buzzed across
the burning Mojave Desert on Saturday in a 135-mile, off-road
motorcycle race that was marred by eleven injuries and has been
opposed by environmentalists.
   Officials of the American Motorcyclists Association charged that
someone had tried to litter the course between Barstow and Las
Vegas with spikes.
   But the four-pronged spikes were dumped on a dummy course that
had been set up to fool protesters, the organizers said.
   Saboteurs also moved some of the course markers, said Ken Boyd
of the association.
   ``They're nothing more than terrorists,'' Boyd said. ``When you
change the course you can take riders over canyons, have them drop
off of cliffs. The riders would have no knowledge of the course.''
   Patricia Schifferle, regional director fo the Wilderness
Society, said the annual race damages topsoil and releases tons of
particulate matter into the air.
   ``We'd like to see this be the last race,'' she said.
   Ms. Schifferle said instructions for riders to stay on the
course for safety and to avoid crushing endangered desert tortoises
are just ``a few token bones tossed to the tortoise for a one-day
joyride.''
   The course was ``ugly,'' said rider Westly Peterson of Los
Angeles. ``It's real dusty, real rough and real short.''
   The race staging area took on the look of a heavy-metal concert
early Saturday with riders and their families, many clad in leather
and chains, arriving before dawn for the race's 7 a.m. start. The
whine of motorcycles reached earsplitting levels as the bikers
revved up, and sand filled the air as the race got under way.
   The Bureau of Land Management said 1,144 motorcyclists and 4,000
to 5,000 spectators and crew members gathered for the event.
   ``It's a zoo, but I love it,'' said referee Ed Hales.
   Three racers suffered serious injuries and were taken to the
Fort Irwin military base hospital, BLM spokeswoman Barbara Maxfield
said. Eight lesser injuries, including dislocated elbows and knees
and broken collarbones, were reported.
   Ms. Maxfield said the race generally took place without
incident, although about 10 riders strayed off course near the
beginning and rode into a wilderness study area.
   ``Other than that it seems to have gone very well,'' she said.
   Ms. Maxfield said BLM officials went over the course both before
and after the race and found no tortoises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
