<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StoreFire     11-25 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Store Fire,0198</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Off-Duty Firefighters Extinguish Blaze in Store</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two off-duty firefighters shopping in a crowded
department store went into action Saturday when someone set fire to
a pillow display, a fire chief said.
   A plastic container filled with a flammable liquid was put in
the display at a Macy's store in the borough of Queens, then
lighted, said Fire Chief William Nagle.
   Firefighters Bill Kregler and Wayne Wright happened to be in the
store shopping separately during the afternoon when they heard
cries of ``Fire!'' and ran to help, Nagle said.
   The two calmed frightened shoppers and tried to put out the fire
with hand-held extinguishers. When that failed, they took over a
store fire hose that two Macy's employees were unraveling.
   By the time Nagle's crew arrived, the fire was out, the chief
said.
   Kregler was taken to a hospital suffering from smoke inhalation,
but was not seriously harmed said St. John's Hospital administrator
Catherine Wilkinson.
   The store's third floor was temporarily evacuated, but there was
no serious damage, Nagle said.
   The fire was ruled arson and fire marshals were investigating,
he said.
</TEXT>
