<FILEID>AP-NR-11-25-89 2257EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Space     11-25 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Space,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Britons Selected for Anglo-Soviet Space Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British man and woman were selected Saturday to
go to the Soviet Union to train for an Anglo-Soviet commercial
space mission. One is to become the first Briton in space.
   Maj. Timothy Mace, 34, and Helen Sharman, 26, were chosen from
among some 13,000 hopefuls who answered newspaper advertisements.
Their selection from among four finalists was announced Saturday by
the Juno space mission in Moscow and relayed in a live television
broadcast to Britain.
   Mace, an advanced instructor in helicopters in the army air
corps, is a British parachuting champion.
   Miss Sharman researches the chemical and physical properties of
chocolate for the Mars candy company and is studying for a
doctorate degree in the luminescence of rare earth ions.
   Both will train but only one will join two Soviet cosmonauts on
the eight-day mission Juno in April 1991. The other is to act as
understudy.
   The mission is the first commercial space flight and is being
financed by international sponsoring companies. During the mission
the crew is to conduct scientific experiments aboard the Mir
station orbiting above the Earth.
   On Thursday, Mace and Miss Sharman fly to the Soviet Union for
an 18-month training program at the Soviet space complex in the
Gagarin Center near Moscow. Each is to be paid about $78,000 by the
fund-raising company Antequaria.
   The mission is scheduled for April 12, 1991 _ the anniversary of
the first manned flight in space, by Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin.
</TEXT>
